May 2019 |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090816171806/http://www.htafc.com/page/ProfilesDetail/0%2C%2C10312~47252%2C00.html Liam Ridehalgh profile] at htafc.com\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Tranmere Rovers F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ridehalgh, Liam}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Halifax, West Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Swindon Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chesterfield F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rotherham United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Tranmere Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liam_Ridehalgh"}
{"title_page": "Horizon (store)", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Horizon\n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = pro\n| image_caption = \n| type = \n| ISIN = \n| ISIN2 = \n| industry = \n| genre = \n| fate = \n| founded = {{Start date and age|1972|08|16}} in [[Metro Toronto]], Canada\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| defunct = {{End date|1979|01}}\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = Canada\n| num_locations = \n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| area_served = Ontario, Quebec\n| key_people = \n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data (if known) -->\n| services = \n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = <!-- Year of revenue data (if known) -->\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = <!-- Year of operating_income data (if known) -->\n| net_income = <!-- or: | profit = -->\n| net_income_year = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (if known) -->\n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = [[T. Eaton Company]]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Horizon''' was a Canadian [[discount store|discount department retailer]], owned by [[T. Eaton Co. Limited]]. Attempting to compete with established Canadian brands like [[Woolco]] and [[Zeller's]] during a downturn in the market, it was T. Eaton's attempt to court \"buyers\", as opposed to \"shoppers\" at its Eaton's stores. Instead, the chain was generally unprofitable, cannibalizing sales from its sister stores, and misplaced, according to analysts. Intended to be a 122-store chain, it only reached 18 locations. The financial drag of the chain in the 1970s is said to have contributed to T. Eaton's significant financial problems in the 1980s.\n\n==History==\n\nIn ''The Globe and Mail'', T. Eaton Co. Ltd. President Robert Butler observed that consumers could be classified as shoppers and buyers. \"Your wife goes out to buy the groceries or a pair of hose or kiddies' underwear, but she goes out to shop for furniture, for interesting gifts, expensive dresses.\"<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\">{{cite news |last1=Picton |first1=John |title=Malls and shopping plazas main attractions as major retailers scramble for new sites |work=The Globe and Mail |date=19 July 1972 |location=Toronto ON |page=B5}}</ref> This insight guided both changes to their main line of stores, but also the creation of Horizon, a discount chain that the company referred to as \"convenience stores.\" It was focused on the \"buyer\" section of the market.<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\" />\n\nStores were to be roughly 60,000 square feet, and either located in neighbourhood malls \"or smaller communities often close to a grocery supermarket.\"<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\" /> The \"'fast-moving' lines of merchandise\" included clothing, \"housewares and notions, sporting goods, small and large appliances and seasonal merchandise.\"<ref name=\"1972-05-25-GM\">{{cite news |last1=Picton |first1=John |title=Eaton's to open a discount chain, 10 stores |work=The Globe and Mail |date=25 May 1972 |location=Toronto ON |page=B1}}</ref> Horizon locations would have centralized check-out counters, versus the in-department desks of the main Eaton's stores.<ref name=\"1978-10-05-TS\">{{cite news |title=Horizon gets the axe |work=The Toronto Star |date=5 October 1978 |location=Toronto ON |page=B12}}</ref>\n\nThe name Horizon \"reflects a forward-looking, contemporary life style\u2014the image these stores will project.\"<ref name=\"1972-05-25-GM\" /> This extended to the store's use of a [[barcode reader]] at checkout, which received media attention;<ref>{{cite web |last1=Geo |first1=Mario |title=Newest in cash registers is checked by John Craig Eaton, left, at opening of new T. Eaton Co. chain called Horizon stores at Sheppard Ave. and Victoria Park Ave. Centre is W. A. (Al) Kelley, general manager. Operating the register is Lynda McElwain, who holds the Magic Wand. The wand scans a special ticket and the register totals the items, figures tax, makes total, all automatically. |url=https://www.torontopubliclibrary.ca/detail.jsp?Entt=RDMDC-TSPA_0110022F&R=DC-TSPA_0110022F |website=Toronto Public Library |accessdate=10 April 2020 |location=Toronto ON |date=1972}}</ref> the store was deemed \"the most automated self-service store in Canada.\"<ref name=\"1972-08-17-GM\">{{cite news |last1=Picton |first1=John |title=First Horizon store's stock sells quickly |work=The Globe and Mail |date=17 August 1972 |location=Toronto ON |page=B1}}</ref> The company also used Eaton's credit cards and computer system, which allowed them to prevent over-spending and keep track of inventory.<ref name=\"1972-08-17-GM\" />\n\nPlans for Horizon were first announced in May 1972.<ref name=\"1972-05-25-GM\" /> The first location was to be in Scarborough, Ontario, opening in August 1972.<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\" /> The earliest stores were meant as a pilot, \"to test different types of community.\"<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\" /> The company planned 122 locations, each intended to have 200,000 people within a ten-minute drive.<ref name=\"rise-fall-172-173\">{{cite book |last1=McQueen |first1=Rod |title=The Eatons : the rise and fall of Canada's royal family |date=1999 |publisher=Stoddart |location=Toronto ON |isbn=0773760784 |pages=172-173 |url=https://archive.org/details/eatonsrisefallof0000mcqu/page/172/mode/2up/search/horizon?q=horizon+eaton%27s |accessdate=10 April 2020 |format=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\nWhile the Scarborough and Yonge-Eglinton locations were successful, the remainder were not, with most locations not adhering to the researched requirements.<ref name=\"rise-fall-172-173\" /> Stores were launched during a general downturn for discounters.<ref name=\"1974-04-20-NP\">{{cite news |last1=Goldenberg |first1=Susan |title=Penney called in to help booster Eaton's Horizon |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48423761/penney-called-in-to-help-bolster/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=National Post |date=20 April 1974 |location=Toronto ON |page=35}}</ref> While the company was privately-owned, woes surrounding its Horizon stores were publicly known, with the ''National Post'' claiming sales dipped after the 1972 Christmas season.<ref name=\"1973-11-10-NP\">{{cite news |last1=Goldenberg |first1=Susan |title=Not lost but cloudy, Horizon dims Eaton's discounting hopes |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48421713/not-lost-but-cloudy-horizon-dims/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=National Post |date=10 November 1973 |location=Toronto ON |page=1}}</ref> Stores were cutting into the sales of traditional Eaton's stores, as opposed to the other discounters.<ref name=\"1973-11-10-NP-part-2\">{{cite news |title=Eaton's Horizon not lost, but cloudy |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48423528/eatons-horizon-not-lost-but-cloudy/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 November 1973 |location=Toronto ON |page=12}}</ref> Horizon brand general manager W. A. Kelley was promoted to vice-president of distribution soon after the stores began operating, part of a larger issue with operations-level turnover.<ref name=\"1973-11-10-NP-part-2\" />\n\n''National Post'' reported that Horizon stopped carrying refrigerators in autumn 1973, as they weren't selling because of the store's lack of delivery service.<ref name=\"1973-11-10-NP\" /> A latter book countered that the store's self-serve format were to blame, as \"...there was no floor staff to explain the different features on something such as a line of refrigerators. That foray wasted another six months as heavy goods were moved into all the stores, then had to be wheeled out against when they failed to sell.\"<ref name=\"rise-fall-172-173\" /> In an attempt to shore up the concept and block competition, Eaton's partnered with [[J. C. Penney]] on a \"joint study\" in 1974.<ref name=\"1974-04-20-NP\" /> In 1975, T. Eaton expected profits for their Horizon division within two years.<ref name=\"1975-03-26-GM\">{{cite news |last1=Howe |first1=Patrick |title=Eaton's public offering will wait for a while |work=The Globe and Mail |date=26 March 1975 |location=Toronto ON |page=B1}}</ref>\n\nT. Eaton decided in January 1976 to end its catalogue division, sparking analyst suggestion that Horizon would be wound down immediately after.<ref name=\"1976-01-15-GM\">{{cite news |last1=Howe |first1=Patrick |title=Simpsons-Sears is seen as big winner in closing of Eaton's catalogue division |work=The Globe and Mail |date=15 January 1976 |location=Toronto ON |page=B3}}</ref>\nT. Eaton announced the end of this format in October 1978, with the transition to be complete by January 1979. Unnamed analysts quoted by the ''Star'' and ''Globe'' suggested that T. Eaton entered the discount too late, after [[K-Mart]], [[Woolco]] and [[Zeller's]] were well-established, and didn't expand enough to be noticed in the market.<ref name=\"1978-10-06-GM\">{{cite news |last1=MacKay |first1=Gillian |title=Eight Horizon outlets to be Eaton's stores |work=The Globe and Mail |date=6 October 1978}}</ref><ref name=\"1978-10-05-TS\" /> The company claimed that the change wasn't representative of the stores' performance, but rather a marketing strategy for smaller suburban stores \"that has been extremely successful in the United States and Australia.\"<ref name=\"1978-10-05-TS\" />\n\nThe six Metro Toronto and two London locations were to be branded as Eaton's, whereas the four Quebec locations would keep the existing brand, but be managed by Eaton's Quebec division.<ref name=\"1978-10-06-GM\" /><ref name=\"1978-10-05-TS\" /> The stores remained smaller than most Eaton's locations, but with the same products and a \"softer\" look.<ref name=\"1978-10-06-GM\" />\n\n===Legacy===\nThe company's poor financials in the 1980s have been attributed to Horizon and its involvement in the [[Eaton Centre#Ontario Downtown Renewal Program (ODRP)|Ontario Downtown Renewal Program]], leading to cuts in the 1980s that sparked unionization in various store locations and a strike in 1985.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wainwright |first1=Kaitlin |title=When strikers stormed Eaton\u2019s flagship department store |url=https://www.tvo.org/article/when-strikers-stormed-eatons-flagship-department-store |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=TVO.org |date=8 March 2019 |location=Toronto ON}}</ref>\n\nSome documentation of the stores survives at the [[Archives of Ontario]], as part of the ''T. Eaton Company fonds''.<ref>The Archives of Ontario's Archives Descriptive Database does not allow static linking. [http://ao.minisisinc.com/scripts/mwimain.dll?get&file=[ARCHON]search.htm Search the database] for ''Horizon stores'' without quotation marks for relevant results.</ref>\n\n==Locations==\n\nThe book ''Eaton's: the Trans-Canada store'' lists 13 Horizon stores,<ref name=\"kopytek\" /> a number that aligns with era media coverage.<ref name=\"1975-03-26-GM\" /> (''The Eatons: the rise and fall of Canada's royal family'' (1999) claims, however, that there were 15 opened.<ref name=\"rise-fall-172-173\" />\n\n* '''Victoria Park and Sheppard''' (Scarborough, Metro Toronto, 16 August 1972)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''[[Westmount Mall]]''' (London, 1 November 1972)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''Northland Shopping Centre''' (London, 1 November 1972)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* Variously listed as either '''Sheridan Mall''' (Mississauga, 15 November 1972)<ref name=\"kopytek\" /> or '''Rockwood Mall'''<ref name=\"1978-10-05-TS\" />\n* '''[[Yonge Eglinton Centre]]''' (Toronto, 27 June 1973)<ref name=\"kopytek\">{{cite book |last1=Kopytek |first1=Bruce Allen |title=Eaton's: the Trans-Canada store |date=21 October 2014 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |URL=https://books.google.ca/books?id=c-12CQAAQBAJ&pg=PT366&lpg=PT366&dq=horizon+eatons&source=bl&ots=PtDJJL4lDP&sig=ACfU3U0bwu26T0l86TlJDc0MaQdjHr1QJA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjlj9OR297oAhUSB50JHaa3BQgQ6AEwEXoECBEQKQ#v=onepage&q=horizon%20eatons&f=false |isbn=1625846959}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Plummer |first1=Kevin |title=Vintage Toronto Ads: British Days at Yonge and Eglinton |url=https://torontoist.com/2007/11/vintage_toronto_41/ |website=Torontoist |accessdate=10 April 2020 |location=Toronto ON |date=20 November 2007}}. Torontoist itself cites ''The North Toronto Herald'', 29 March 1974.</ref>\n* '''[[Dufferin Mall|Dufferin Plaza]]''' (Toronto, 26 September 1973)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''[[List of shopping malls in Greater Longueuil#Galeries Taschereau|Greenfield Park]]''' (Montreal, 15 November 1973)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''Les Galeries St-Laurent''' (Montreal, 15 November 1973)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''Les Galeries des Mille-Iles''' (Rosemere, 15 November 1973)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''Rexdale Plaza''' (Etobicoke, Metro Toronto, 2 October 1973):<ref name=\"kopytek\" /> This location was intended to be the second opened in the chain.<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\" />\n* '''[[Beloeil, Quebec#Economy|Place Montenach]]''' (Beloil, 6 March 1974)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''[[List of small shopping centres in Montreal#Centre Domaine|Centre Domaine]]''' (Montreal, 6 March 1974)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''Gerrard Square'''<ref>{{cite web |title=The Rotting Decaying Corpse of Zellers Gerrard Square |url=http://photoblair.blogspot.com/2012/10/the-rotting-decaying-corpse-of-zellers.html |website=Photoblair.ca |accessdate=11 April 2020 |location=[Toronto ON] |date=27 October 2012}}</ref> (Toronto, 14 August 1974)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Eaton's]]\n[[Category:Defunct department stores]]\n[[Category:Defunct retail companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Department stores of Canada]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Retail companies disestablished in 1979]]\n[[Category:1972 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:1979 disestablishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:1979 disestablishments in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Horizon\n| logo = \n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = pro\n| image_caption = \n| type = \n| ISIN = \n| ISIN2 = \n| industry = \n| genre = \n| fate = \n| founded = {{Start date and age|1972|08|16}} in [[Metro Toronto]], Canada\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| defunct = {{End date|1979|01}}\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = \n| hq_location_country = Canada\n| num_locations = \n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| area_served = Ontario, Quebec\n| key_people = \n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data (if known) -->\n| services = \n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = <!-- Year of revenue data (if known) -->\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = <!-- Year of operating_income data (if known) -->\n| net_income = <!-- or: | profit = -->\n| net_income_year = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (if known) -->\n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = [[T. Eaton Company]]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Horizon''' was a Canadian [[discount store|discount department retailer]], owned by [[T. Eaton Co. Limited]]. Attempting to compete with established Canadian brands like [[Woolco]] and [[Zeller's]] during a downturn in the market, it was T. Eaton's attempt to court \"buyers\", as opposed to \"shoppers\" at its Eaton's stores. Instead, the chain was generally unprofitable, cannibalizing sales from its sister stores, and misplaced, according to analysts. Intended to be a 122-store chain, it only reached 18 locations. The financial drag of the chain in the 1970s is said to have contributed to T. Eaton's significant financial problems in the 1980s.\n\n==History==\n\nIn ''The Globe and Mail'', T. Eaton Co. Ltd. President Robert Butler observed that consumers could be classified as shoppers and buyers. \"Your wife goes out to buy the groceries or a pair of hose or kiddies' underwear, but she goes out to shop for furniture, for interesting gifts, expensive dresses.\"<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\">{{cite news |last1=Picton |first1=John |title=Malls and shopping plazas main attractions as major retailers scramble for new sites |work=The Globe and Mail |date=19 July 1972 |location=Toronto ON |page=B5}}</ref> This insight guided both changes to their main line of stores, but also the creation of Horizon, a discount chain that the company referred to as \"convenience stores.\" It was focused on the \"buyer\" section of the market.<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\" />\n\nStores were to be roughly 60,000 square feet, and either located in neighbourhood malls \"or smaller communities often close to a grocery supermarket.\"<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\" /> The \"'fast-moving' lines of merchandise\" included clothing, \"housewares and notions, sporting goods, small and large appliances and seasonal merchandise.\"<ref name=\"1972-05-25-GM\">{{cite news |last1=Picton |first1=John |title=Eaton's to open a discount chain, 10 stores |work=The Globe and Mail |date=25 May 1972 |location=Toronto ON |page=B1}}</ref> Horizon locations would have centralized check-out counters, versus the in-department desks of the main Eaton's stores.<ref name=\"1978-10-05-TS\">{{cite news |title=Horizon gets the axe |work=The Toronto Star |date=5 October 1978 |location=Toronto ON |page=B12}}</ref>\n\nThe name Horizon \"reflects a forward-looking, contemporary life style\u2014the image these stores will project.\"<ref name=\"1972-05-25-GM\" /> This extended to the store's use of a [[barcode reader]] at checkout, which received media attention;<ref>{{cite web |last1=Geo |first1=Mario |title=Newest in cash registers is checked by John Craig Eaton, left, at opening of new T. Eaton Co. chain called Horizon stores at Sheppard Ave. and Victoria Park Ave. Centre is W. A. (Al) Kelley, general manager. Operating the register is Lynda McElwain, who holds the Magic Wand. The wand scans a special ticket and the register totals the items, figures tax, makes total, all automatically. |url=https://www.torontopubliclibrary.ca/detail.jsp?Entt=RDMDC-TSPA_0110022F&R=DC-TSPA_0110022F |website=Toronto Public Library |accessdate=10 April 2020 |location=Toronto ON |date=1972}}</ref> the store was deemed \"the most automated self-service store in Canada.\"<ref name=\"1972-08-17-GM\">{{cite news |last1=Picton |first1=John |title=First Horizon store's stock sells quickly |work=The Globe and Mail |date=17 August 1972 |location=Toronto ON |page=B1}}</ref> The company also used Eaton's credit cards and computer system, which allowed them to prevent over-spending and keep track of inventory.<ref name=\"1972-08-17-GM\" />\n\nPlans for Horizon were first announced in May 1972.<ref name=\"1972-05-25-GM\" /> The first location was to be in Scarborough, Ontario, opening in August 1972.<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\" /> The earliest stores were meant as a pilot, \"to test different types of community.\"<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\" /> The company planned 122 locations, each intended to have 200,000 people within a ten-minute drive.<ref name=\"rise-fall-172-173\">{{cite book |last1=McQueen |first1=Rod |title=The Eatons : the rise and fall of Canada's royal family |date=1999 |publisher=Stoddart |location=Toronto ON |isbn=0773760784 |pages=172-173 |url=https://archive.org/details/eatonsrisefallof0000mcqu/page/172/mode/2up/search/horizon?q=horizon+eaton%27s |accessdate=10 April 2020 |format=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\nWhile the Scarborough and Yonge-Eglinton locations were successful, the remainder were not, with most locations not adhering to the researched requirements.<ref name=\"rise-fall-172-173\" /> Stores were launched during a general downturn for discounters.<ref name=\"1974-04-20-NP\">{{cite news |last1=Goldenberg |first1=Susan |title=Penney called in to help booster Eaton's Horizon |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48423761/penney-called-in-to-help-bolster/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=National Post |date=20 April 1974 |location=Toronto ON |page=35}}</ref> While the company was privately-owned, woes surrounding its Horizon stores were publicly known, with the ''National Post'' claiming sales dipped after the 1972 Christmas season.<ref name=\"1973-11-10-NP\">{{cite news |last1=Goldenberg |first1=Susan |title=Not lost but cloudy, Horizon dims Eaton's discounting hopes |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48421713/not-lost-but-cloudy-horizon-dims/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=National Post |date=10 November 1973 |location=Toronto ON |page=1}}</ref> Stores were cutting into the sales of traditional Eaton's stores, as opposed to the other discounters.<ref name=\"1973-11-10-NP-part-2\">{{cite news |title=Eaton's Horizon not lost, but cloudy |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48423528/eatons-horizon-not-lost-but-cloudy/ |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=10 November 1973 |location=Toronto ON |page=12}}</ref> Horizon brand general manager W. A. Kelley was promoted to vice-president of distribution soon after the stores began operating, part of a larger issue with operations-level turnover.<ref name=\"1973-11-10-NP-part-2\" />\n\n''National Post'' reported that Horizon stopped carrying refrigerators in autumn 1973, as they weren't selling because of the store's lack of delivery service.<ref name=\"1973-11-10-NP\" /> A latter book countered that the store's self-serve format were to blame, as \"...there was no floor staff to explain the different features on something such as a line of refrigerators. That foray wasted another six months as heavy goods were moved into all the stores, then had to be wheeled out against when they failed to sell.\"<ref name=\"rise-fall-172-173\" /> In an attempt to shore up the concept and block competition, Eaton's partnered with [[J. C. Penney]] on a \"joint study\" in 1974.<ref name=\"1974-04-20-NP\" /> In 1975, T. Eaton expected profits for their Horizon division within two years.<ref name=\"1975-03-26-GM\">{{cite news |last1=Howe |first1=Patrick |title=Eaton's public offering will wait for a while |work=The Globe and Mail |date=26 March 1975 |location=Toronto ON |page=B1}}</ref>\n\nT. Eaton decided in January 1976 to end its catalogue division, sparking analyst suggestion that Horizon would be wound down immediately after.<ref name=\"1976-01-15-GM\">{{cite news |last1=Howe |first1=Patrick |title=Simpsons-Sears is seen as big winner in closing of Eaton's catalogue division |work=The Globe and Mail |date=15 January 1976 |location=Toronto ON |page=B3}}</ref>\nT. Eaton announced the end of this format in October 1978, with the transition to be complete by January 1979. Unnamed analysts quoted by the ''Star'' and ''Globe'' suggested that T. Eaton entered the discount too late, after [[K-Mart]], [[Woolco]] and [[Zeller's]] were well-established, and didn't expand enough to be noticed in the market.<ref name=\"1978-10-06-GM\">{{cite news |last1=MacKay |first1=Gillian |title=Eight Horizon outlets to be Eaton's stores |work=The Globe and Mail |date=6 October 1978}}</ref><ref name=\"1978-10-05-TS\" /> The company claimed that the change wasn't representative of the stores' performance, but rather a marketing strategy for smaller suburban stores \"that has been extremely successful in the United States and Australia.\"<ref name=\"1978-10-05-TS\" />\n\nThe six Metro Toronto and two London locations were to be branded as Eaton's, whereas the four Quebec locations would keep the existing brand, but be managed by Eaton's Quebec division.<ref name=\"1978-10-06-GM\" /><ref name=\"1978-10-05-TS\" /> The stores remained smaller than most Eaton's locations, but with the same products and a \"softer\" look.<ref name=\"1978-10-06-GM\" />\n\n===Legacy===\nThe company's poor financials in the 1980s have been attributed to Horizon and its involvement in the [[Eaton Centre#Ontario Downtown Renewal Program (ODRP)|Ontario Downtown Renewal Program]], leading to cuts in the 1980s that sparked unionization in various store locations and a strike in 1985.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wainwright |first1=Kaitlin |title=When strikers stormed Eaton\u2019s flagship department store |url=https://www.tvo.org/article/when-strikers-stormed-eatons-flagship-department-store |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=TVO.org |date=8 March 2019 |location=Toronto ON}}</ref>\n\nSome documentation of the stores survives at the [[Archives of Ontario]], as part of the ''T. Eaton Company fonds''.<ref>The Archives of Ontario's Archives Descriptive Database does not allow static linking. [http://ao.minisisinc.com/scripts/mwimain.dll?get&file=[ARCHON]search.htm Search the database] for ''Horizon stores'' without quotation marks for relevant results.</ref>\n\n==Locations==\n\nThe book ''Eaton's: the Trans-Canada store'' lists 13 Horizon stores,<ref name=\"kopytek\" /> a number that aligns with era media coverage.<ref name=\"1975-03-26-GM\" /> (''The Eatons: the rise and fall of Canada's royal family'' (1999) claims, however, that there were 15 opened.<ref name=\"rise-fall-172-173\" />\n\n* '''Victoria Park and Sheppard''' (Scarborough, Metro Toronto, 16 August 1972)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''[[Westmount Mall]]''' (London, 1 November 1972)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''Northland Shopping Centre''' (London, 1 November 1972)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''Sheridan Mall''' (Mississauga, 15 November 1972)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''[[Yonge Eglinton Centre]]''' (Toronto, 27 June 1973)<ref name=\"kopytek\">{{cite book |last1=Kopytek |first1=Bruce Allen |title=Eaton's: the Trans-Canada store |date=21 October 2014 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |URL=https://books.google.ca/books?id=c-12CQAAQBAJ&pg=PT366&lpg=PT366&dq=horizon+eatons&source=bl&ots=PtDJJL4lDP&sig=ACfU3U0bwu26T0l86TlJDc0MaQdjHr1QJA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjlj9OR297oAhUSB50JHaa3BQgQ6AEwEXoECBEQKQ#v=onepage&q=horizon%20eatons&f=false |isbn=1625846959}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Plummer |first1=Kevin |title=Vintage Toronto Ads: British Days at Yonge and Eglinton |url=https://torontoist.com/2007/11/vintage_toronto_41/ |website=Torontoist |accessdate=10 April 2020 |location=Toronto ON |date=20 November 2007}}. Torontoist itself cites ''The North Toronto Herald'', 29 March 1974.</ref>\n* '''[[Dufferin Mall|Dufferin Plaza]]''' (Toronto, 26 September 1973)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''[[List of shopping malls in Greater Longueuil#Galeries Taschereau|Greenfield Park]]''' (Montreal, 15 November 1973)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''Les Galeries St-Laurent''' (Montreal, 15 November 1973)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''Les Galeries des Mille-Iles''' (Rosemere, 15 November 1973)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''Rexdale Plaza''' (Etobicoke, Metro Toronto, 2 October 1973):<ref name=\"kopytek\" /> This location was intended to be the second opened in the chain.<ref name=\"1972-07-19-GM\" />\n* '''[[Beloeil, Quebec#Economy|Place Montenach]]''' (Beloil, 6 March 1974)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''[[List of small shopping centres in Montreal#Centre Domaine|Centre Domaine]]''' (Montreal, 6 March 1974)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n* '''Gerrard Square'''<ref>{{cite web |title=The Rotting Decaying Corpse of Zellers Gerrard Square |url=http://photoblair.blogspot.com/2012/10/the-rotting-decaying-corpse-of-zellers.html |website=Photoblair.ca |accessdate=11 April 2020 |location=[Toronto ON] |date=27 October 2012}}</ref> (Toronto, 14 August 1974)<ref name=\"kopytek\" />\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Eaton's]]\n[[Category:Defunct department stores]]\n[[Category:Defunct retail companies of Canada]]\n[[Category:Department stores of Canada]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1972]]\n[[Category:Retail companies disestablished in 1979]]\n[[Category:1972 establi