{"title_page": "Ala", "text_new": "'''Ala Ramadan''' or '''\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0621 \u0631\u0645\u0636\u0627\u0646''' may refer to:\n{{TOC right}}\n\n== Places ==\n* [[Alabama]], a state in the United States\n* [[Ala, Hiiu County]], Estonia, a village\n* [[Ala, Valga County]], Estonia, a village\n* [[Ala, Alappuzha]], Kerala, India, a village\n* [[Ala, Iran]], a village in Semnan Province\n* [[Ala, Gotland]], a settlement on the Swedish island of Gotland\n* Ala, alternate name of [[Alad]], a village in Khuzestan Province, Iran\n* [[Ala, Trentino]], Italy, a comune\n* [[Al\u00e0 dei Sardi]] (in Sardinian: Al\u00e0), Italy, a comune\n* [[Alae (Cilicia)]], a town of ancient Cilicia\n\n== Science ==\n* [[Acetylated lanolin alcohol]]\n* [[Ala of nose]]\n* [[Alae (anatomy)]] or ala, a feature of the anatomy of many nematodes worms\n* [[Alanine]], an \u03b1-amino acid\n* [[Alpha lipoic acid]], a nutritional supplement\n* [[Alpha-linolenic acid]], an omega-3 fatty acid\n* Ala, the alar part of a [[nasalis muscle]]\n* [[\u03b4-aminolevulinic acid]] or \u03b4-ALA\n* Members of the [[P4-ATPase]] family in ''Arabidopsis thaliana'': Aminophospholipid ATPase (ALA)\n\n== Mythology and religion ==\n* [[Ala (demon)]], a female demon in Serbian mythology\n* [[Ala (Luwian goddess)]], a Hittite and Luwian goddess\n* [[Ala (Odinani)]], an Alusi (deity) in the Odinani beliefs of the Igbo people of Nigeria\n\n== Military ==\n* {{USS|Ala|YT-139}}, a US Navy tugboat\n* [[Ala (Roman allied military unit)]], a Republican-period, largely infantry, formation of 5,400 men\n* [[Ala (Roman cavalry unit)]], an Imperial-period, purely cavalry, formation of 500 men\n\n== ALA ==\n* [[Active Line Access]], a standard for supply of services in fibre networks\n*Aerodinamica Lamborghini Attiva, [[Lamborghini]]'s active aerodynamic system\n* [[Aerotransportes Litoral Argentino]], a former Argentinian airline; see [[Austral L\u00edneas A\u00e9reas]]<!--OK if 1st link red-->\n* [[African Leadership Academy]]\n* [[American Leadership Academy]]\n* [[Liberal Popular Alliance]], an Italian political party\n* [[Allgemeine Anzeigen GmbH]]\n* [[American Latvian Association]]\n* [[American Legion Auxiliary]]\n* [[American Library Association]]\n* [[American Literature Association]]\n* [[American Lung Association]]\n* [[Arab Liberation Army]]\n* [[Arakan Liberation Army]]\n* [[Arizona Lutheran Academy]]\n* [[Chartered Institute of Library and Information Professionals#History|Associate of the Library Association]]\n* [[Association for Laboratory Automation]]\n* [[Atlas of Living Australia]], on online data resource for plants and animals found in [[Australia]]\n* [[Austral L\u00edneas A\u00e9reas]], an Argentine domestic airline\n* [[Australian Lacrosse Association]]\n* [[Automobile Legal Association]], a former American automobile club similar to the [[American Automobile Association|AAA]]<!--OK if 1st link red-->\n*[[Australian Liberty Alliance]], a political party\n\n== Codes ==\n* [[\u00c5land Islands]]' ISO 3166-1 country code\n* [[Alcatel-Lucent|Alcatel]]'s former NYSE stock symbol\n* [[Almaty International Airport]]'s IATA code\n\n== People ==\n* [[Ala al-Din Atsiz]] (died 1214), Sultan of the Ghurid dynasty from 1213 to 1214\n* [[Ala al-Din Ali]], last Sultan of the Ghurid dynasty, from 1214 to 1215\n* [[Kayqubad I]] or Al\u0101 ad-D\u012bn Kayqub\u0101d bin Kayk\u0101v\u016bs (1188\u20131237), Seljuq Sultan of R\u00fbm\n* Ala al-Din Abu al-Hassan Ali ibn Abi-Hazm al-Qurashi al-Dimashq, or [[Ibn al-Nafis]], (1213\u20131288), Arab Muslim polymath\n* [[Ata-Malik Juvayni]] (in full: Ala al-Din Ata-ullah) (1226\u20131283), Persian historian\n* Al\u0101 ud-D\u012bn [[Atsiz]], Khwarazm Shah from 1127 until his death in 1156\n* [[Ala ad-Din Tekish]], (died 1200), Khwarazm Shah from 1172\n* Ala ad-Din [[Muhammad II of Khwarezm]] (died 1221), Khwarazm Shah from 1200\n* [[Ala ud din Masud]], Sultan of Delhi from 1242 to 1246\n* [[Ala ud-Daula Simnani]] (1261\u20131336), Persian S\u016bf\u012b, writer and teacher\n* [[Ala Al-Kuwaikabi]] (born 1980), Saudi Arabian former footballer\n* [[Ala Al-Sasi]] (born 1987), Yemeni footballer\n* [[Ala Bashir]] (born 1939), Iraqi painter, sculptor and plastic surgeon\n* [[Ala Boratyn]] (born 1992), Polish singer also known as simply Ala\n* [[Ala M\u00e2nd\u00e2canu]] (born 1954), Moldovan politician and journalist\n* [[Weld El 15]], Tunisian rapper born Ala Yaacoubi\n* [[Efkan Ala]] (born 1965), Turkish civil servant and government minister\n* [[Hossein Ala']] (1882\u20131964), former prime minister of Iran\n* [[Alaa Abd El-Fatah]], Egyptian blogger\n* [[Alaa Abdelnaby]], Egyptian-American retired professional basketball player, current broadcaster/analyst \n* [[Alaa Batayneh]], Jordanian businessman and politician\n* [[Alaa Gatea]], Iraqi footballer\n* [[Alaa Ibrahim]], Egyptian footballer\n* [[Alaa Mubarak]], Egyptian businessman\n* [[Alaa Murabit]], Canadian Physician, Commissioner\n* [[Alaa Al Shbli]], Syrian footballer\n* [[Alaa Al-Zahra]], Iraqi footballer\n\n== Other uses ==\n* 'Al\u00e1', the last month of the [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed calendar]]\n* ''[[A List Apart]]'', a webzine for web designers\n* ALA, the short name of the [[Alaska Aces (PBA)|Alaska Aces]], a team at the Philippine Basketball Association\n\n== See also ==\n* [[\u00e0 la]], French for 'in the style/manner of' commonly used in English\n* [[Al-Ala]], the 87th chapter of the Qur'an\n* [[Ala Industrial Zone]], Iran, a village\n* [[Ala da\u011flar\u0131]], a mountain range in the Taurus chain, Turkey\n* [[Ala railway station]], Pakistan\n* [[Allah]], Arabic name for God\n* [[Ala\u00e2, Tunisia]], a town in Kairouan Governorate, Tunisia\n\n{{disambiguation|geo|given name|surname}}\n\n[[Category:Arabic masculine given names]]\n", "text_old": "'''Ala''' or '''Alae''' may refer to:\n{{TOC right}}\n\n== Places ==\n* [[Alabama]], a state in the United States\n* [[Ala, Hiiu County]], Estonia, a village\n* [[Ala, Valga County]], Estonia, a village\n* [[Ala, Alappuzha]], Kerala, India, a village\n* [[Ala, Iran]], a village in Semnan Province\n* [[Ala, Gotland]], a settlement on the Swedish island of Gotland\n* Ala, alternate name of [[Alad]], a village in Khuzestan Province, Iran\n* [[Ala, Trentino]], Italy, a comune\n* [[Al\u00e0 dei Sardi]] (in Sardinian: Al\u00e0), Italy, a comune\n* [[Alae (Cilicia)]], a town of ancient Cilicia\n\n== Science ==\n* [[Acetylated lanolin alcohol]]\n* [[Ala of nose]]\n* [[Alae (anatomy)]] or ala, a feature of the anatomy of many nematodes worms\n* [[Alanine]], an \u03b1-amino acid\n* [[Alpha lipoic acid]], a nutritional supplement\n* [[Alpha-linolenic acid]], an omega-3 fatty acid\n* Ala, the alar part of a [[nasalis muscle]]\n* [[\u03b4-aminolevulinic acid]] or \u03b4-ALA\n* Members of the [[P4-ATPase]] family in ''Arabidopsis thaliana'': Aminophospholipid ATPase (ALA)\n\n== Mythology and religion ==\n* [[Ala (demon)]], a female demon in Serbian mythology\n* [[Ala (Luwian goddess)]], a Hittite and Luwian goddess\n* [[Ala (Odinani)]], an Alusi (deity) in the Odinani beliefs of the Igbo people of Nigeria\n\n== Military ==\n* {{USS|Ala|YT-139}}, a US Navy tugboat\n* [[Ala (Roman allied military unit)]], a Republican-period, largely infantry, formation of 5,400 men\n* [[Ala (Roman cavalry unit)]], an Imperial-period, purely cavalry, formation of 500 men\n\n== ALA ==\n* [[Active Line Access]], a standard for supply of services in fibre networks\n*Aerodinamica Lamborghini Attiva, [[Lamborghini]]'s active aerodynamic system\n* [[Aerotransportes Litoral Argentino]], a former Argentinian airline; see [[Austral L\u00edneas A\u00e9reas]]<!--OK if 1st link red-->\n* [[African Leadership Academy]]\n* [[American Leadership Academy]]\n* [[Liberal Popular Alliance]], an Italian political party\n* [[Allgemeine Anzeigen GmbH]]\n* [[American Latvian Association]]\n* [[American Legion Auxiliary]]\n* [[American Library Association]]\n* [[American Literature Association]]\n* [[American Lung Association]]\n* [[Arab Liberation Army]]\n* [[Arakan Liberation Army]]\n* [[Arizona Lutheran Academy]]\n* [[Chartered Institute of Library and Information Professionals#History|Associate of the Library Association]]\n* [[Association for Laboratory Automation]]\n* [[Atlas of Living Australia]], on online data resource for plants and animals found in [[Australia]]\n* [[Austral L\u00edneas A\u00e9reas]], an Argentine domestic airline\n* [[Australian Lacrosse Association]]\n* [[Automobile Legal Association]], a former American automobile club similar to the [[American Automobile Association|AAA]]<!--OK if 1st link red-->\n*[[Australian Liberty Alliance]], a political party\n\n== Codes ==\n* [[\u00c5land Islands]]' ISO 3166-1 country code\n* [[Alcatel-Lucent|Alcatel]]'s former NYSE stock symbol\n* [[Almaty International Airport]]'s IATA code\n\n== People ==\n* [[Ala al-Din Atsiz]] (died 1214), Sultan of the Ghurid dynasty from 1213 to 1214\n* [[Ala al-Din Ali]], last Sultan of the Ghurid dynasty, from 1214 to 1215\n* [[Kayqubad I]] or Al\u0101 ad-D\u012bn Kayqub\u0101d bin Kayk\u0101v\u016bs (1188\u20131237), Seljuq Sultan of R\u00fbm\n* Ala al-Din Abu al-Hassan Ali ibn Abi-Hazm al-Qurashi al-Dimashq, or [[Ibn al-Nafis]], (1213\u20131288), Arab Muslim polymath\n* [[Ata-Malik Juvayni]] (in full: Ala al-Din Ata-ullah) (1226\u20131283), Persian historian\n* Al\u0101 ud-D\u012bn [[Atsiz]], Khwarazm Shah from 1127 until his death in 1156\n* [[Ala ad-Din Tekish]], (died 1200), Khwarazm Shah from 1172\n* Ala ad-Din [[Muhammad II of Khwarezm]] (died 1221), Khwarazm Shah from 1200\n* [[Ala ud din Masud]], Sultan of Delhi from 1242 to 1246\n* [[Ala ud-Daula Simnani]] (1261\u20131336), Persian S\u016bf\u012b, writer and teacher\n* [[Ala Al-Kuwaikabi]] (born 1980), Saudi Arabian former footballer\n* [[Ala Al-Sasi]] (born 1987), Yemeni footballer\n* [[Ala Bashir]] (born 1939), Iraqi painter, sculptor and plastic surgeon\n* [[Ala Boratyn]] (born 1992), Polish singer also known as simply Ala\n* [[Ala M\u00e2nd\u00e2canu]] (born 1954), Moldovan politician and journalist\n* [[Weld El 15]], Tunisian rapper born Ala Yaacoubi\n* [[Efkan Ala]] (born 1965), Turkish civil servant and government minister\n* [[Hossein Ala']] (1882\u20131964), former prime minister of Iran\n* [[Alaa Abd El-Fatah]], Egyptian blogger\n* [[Alaa Abdelnaby]], Egyptian-American retired professional basketball player, current broadcaster/analyst \n* [[Alaa Batayneh]], Jordanian businessman and politician\n* [[Alaa Gatea]], Iraqi footballer\n* [[Alaa Ibrahim]], Egyptian footballer\n* [[Alaa Mubarak]], Egyptian businessman\n* [[Alaa Murabit]], Canadian Physician, Commissioner\n* [[Alaa Al Shbli]], Syrian footballer\n* [[Alaa Al-Zahra]], Iraqi footballer\n\n== Other uses ==\n* 'Al\u00e1', the last month of the [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed calendar]]\n* ''[[A List Apart]]'', a webzine for web designers\n* ALA, the short name of the [[Alaska Aces (PBA)|Alaska Aces]], a team at the Philippine Basketball Association\n\n== See also ==\n* [[\u00e0 la]], French for 'in the style/manner of' commonly used in English\n* [[Al-Ala]], the 87th chapter of the Qur'an\n* [[Ala Industrial Zone]], Iran, a village\n* [[Ala da\u011flar\u0131]], a mountain range in the Taurus chain, Turkey\n* [[Ala railway station]], Pakistan\n* [[Allah]], Arabic name for God\n* [[Ala\u00e2, Tunisia]], a town in Kairouan Governorate, Tunisia\n\n{{disambiguation|geo|given name|surname}}\n\n[[Category:Arabic masculine given names]]\n", "name_user": "212.237.118.91", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ala"}
{"title_page": "The Russell Brand Show prank telephone calls row", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''The Russell Brand Show'' prank telephone calls row}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right;margin-left:1em;text-align:center;\"\n|-\n| style=\"width:33%;\"| [[Image:Russell Brand Arthur Premier.jpg|110px]]\n| style=\"width:33%;\"| [[Image:JonathanRoss.jpg|110px]]\n| style=\"width:33%;\"| [[Image:Andrew sachs.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n! <small>[[Russell Brand]]</small>\n! <small>[[Jonathan Ross]]</small>\n! <small>[[Andrew Sachs]]</small>\n|}\nIn an episode of [[BBC Radio 2|BBC Radio 2's]] ''[[The Russell Brand Show (radio show)|The Russell Brand Show]]'' broadcast on Saturday 18 October 2008, comedian [[Russell Brand]] and presenter [[Jonathan Ross]] made [[prank call]]s to actor [[Andrew Sachs]] that led to controversy in the United Kingdom. Brand and Ross called Sachs to interview him on-air; when he did not answer, they left a series of lewd messages on his answering machine, including comments about Brand's relationship with Sachs' granddaughter, Georgina Baillie. After initially receiving little attention, a 26 October article in ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' led to widespread criticism of Brand, Ross and the editorial decisions of the [[BBC]], with the event becoming known as \"'''Sachsgate'''\" or \"'''Manuelgate'''\" (a reference to Sachs' [[Manuel (Fawlty Towers)|character]] in ''[[Fawlty Towers]]'').<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/sachsgate-obscene-prank-calls-russell-9376380|title=Andrew Sachs was 'haunted' by obscene calls from Russell Brand and Jonathan Ross|last=Rutter|first=Claire|date=2016-12-02|work=mirror|access-date=2017-08-12}}</ref>\n\nBrand and Ross were criticised by a number of [[Members of Parliament]], including [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]], and the BBC received a record number of complaints. The BBC suspended Ross while it and [[Ofcom]] launched investigations. Both Brand and Radio 2 controller [[Lesley Douglas]] resigned from the BBC. On 30 October, the BBC suspended Ross without pay for 12 weeks. The BBC was fined \u00a3150,000 by Ofcom.<ref>{{cite news|last=Holmwood|first=Leigh|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/apr/03/russell-brand-jonathan-ross-bbc-fine|title=BBC fined \u00a3150,000 over Russell Brand and Jonathan Ross phone prank scandal|work=The Guardian|accessdate=3 April 2009|location=London, UK}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nFrom April 2006 through to October 2008, [[Russell Brand]] presented the weekly BBC radio show [[The Russell Brand Show (radio show)|''The Russell Brand Show'']]. In most episodes Brand was joined by his co-host [[Matt Morgan (comedian)|Matt Morgan]] who would often steer him in certain directions regarding what to talk about. Brand sometimes called in a variety of his celebrity friends as well, including [[Noel Fielding]], [[Jonah Hill]] and [[Morrissey]], to talk on the show each week.\n\nOn 11 October 2008, [[David Baddiel]] co-hosted Brand's show. Baddiel recalled having met Georgina Baillie at Brand's home and being told that her grandfather was actor [[Andrew Sachs]]. According to Baddiel, Baillie said \"Don't tell him I was here!\"<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC apologises for lewd phone calls by Russell Brand and Jonathan Ross|date=28 October 2008|work=[[The Times]]|author=Patrick Foster|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5022840.ece | location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Prank calls==\n\nOn Thursday 16 October 2008, Sachs, who famously portrayed [[Manuel (Fawlty Towers)|Manuel]] in television comedy ''[[Fawlty Towers]]'', was scheduled to be a phone-in guest on Brand's evening radio show.  The show was to be pre-recorded due to Brand's work commitments.<ref name=\"bbcApology\"/>\n\nAfter being unable to reach Sachs on his home telephone, Brand and his co-host of the week, fellow Radio 2 DJ [[Jonathan Ross]], left Sachs four voice messages. In the first message, Brand joked about ''Fawlty Towers'' and the fact that both he and Sachs had appeared in ''[[The Bill]]'', but was interrupted by Ross shouting out \"he fucked your granddaughter\". The rest of the message and the following three messages were all characterised by Brand and Ross attempting to apologise for Ross' outburst, but each quickly descended into farce, with, for example, Brand singing to Sachs: \"It was consensual and she wasn't menstrual\" and Ross asking to marry him.<ref name=\"bbcApology\"/>  Brand later said that listening to those calls is like hearing \"two idiots dancing towards a canyon\"; however no complaints were received.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4289499/Russell-Brand-jokes-about-Andrew-Sachs-scandal-in-new-comedy-gig.html |title=Russell Brand jokes about Andrew Sachs scandal in new comedy gig |work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London |first=Aislinn |last=Simpson |date=19 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Complaints==\nOn 25 October, Brand presented his last edition of his radio show with co-host [[Simon Amstell]], which they performed live. Shortly before going on air, Brand was informed that ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' would be running a story about the phone calls. During the show, Brand apologised to Sachs, but also devoted much of the show to deriding the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' for its support of [[Nazism]] in the run up to [[World War II]]. Even in his apology to Sachs, Brand stated \"what's worse \u2013 leaving a swearword on [[Andrew Sachs]]' answerphone or tacitly supporting [[Adolf Hitler]] when he took charge of the [[Third Reich]]?\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/27/russell-brand-daily-mail-fawlty-towers |title=Russell Brand highlights Mail Hitler links in apology to Fawlty Towers star |date=27 October 2008 |work=The Guardian |location=London |first=John |last=Plunkett}}</ref>\n\nThe incident escalated into a media and political storm that, in much of the British media, eclipsed news of the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|global financial crisis]], the [[2008 United States presidential election|US Presidential election]], and [[2008 Nord-Kivu fighting|fighting in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC suspends top stars in media storm|date=29 October 2008|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|url=http://currentaffairs.ninemsn.com.au./article.aspx?id=657414}}</ref>\n\nSachs later stated he had not given permission for the messages to be broadcast.<ref name=\"Telegraph29Oct08\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/3278635/Jonathan-Ross-and-Russell-Brand-suspended-by-BBC-over-Andrew-Sachs-calls.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|title=Jonathan Ross and Russell Brand suspended by BBC over Andrew Sachs calls|date=29 October 2008|accessdate=29 October 2008|author=Anita Singh | location=London}}</ref> The BBC originally stated that they were \"not aware of any complaint by Mr Sachs\", but later confirmed a complaint had been received, and apologised.<ref name=\"bbcApology\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7692911.stm|title=BBC apologises over Brand prank|date=27 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=27 October 2008}}</ref> Brand issued an apology for making the calls<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7691641.stm|title=Brand 'sorry' for telephone stunt|publisher=BBC|date=26 October 2008}}</ref> but stated it was \"funny\" during his last radio show, before the ''Mail'' had printed the story.<ref name=\"bbcApology\" /> [[Ofcom]], the telecommunications regulator, announced its own investigation.<ref>{{cite news|author=Rob Shepherd|title= Pressure mounts over Ross and Brand phone prank|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/2008/10/pressure_mounts_over_ross_and_brand_phone_prank.html|work= [[Broadcast Now]]|date=28 October 2008|accessdate=28 October 2008}}</ref> On 28 October 2008, the BBC said that it had received 4,700 complaints,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7694921.stm|title=Ofcom to launch BBC Brand inquiry|date=28 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 October 2008}}</ref> after the calls became international news.<ref name=\"NME29Oct08\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-killers/40721|title=Killers and Glasvegas caught-up in Jonathan Ross and Russell Brand's BBC ban|date=29 October 2008|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref><ref name=Times2 /> Later the same day, this number had passed 10,000.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7694989.stm|title=Timeline: Russell Brand prank calls|publisher=BBC|date=30 October 2008}}</ref> The same afternoon, [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] called the incident \"clearly inappropriate and unacceptable\".<ref name=\"sack\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7696714.stm|title=BBC pressured to sack presenters|date=29 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref> The following day the number of complaints was said to have topped 18,000.<ref name=\"timeline\"/>\n\nThis incident resulted in the second-highest number of complaints to the BBC in recent years, second only to its airing of ''[[Jerry Springer: The Opera]]''.<ref name=Times2>{{cite news|title=Tories demand Commons debate on BBC 'Manuelgate'|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=30 October 2008|author=Philippe Naughton|url=http://timesonline.co.uk./tol/news/uk/article5047594.ece|publisher=News International Limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Offence record: The most complained-about shows|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 October 2008|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/29/russell-brand-jonathan-ross-complaints|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=This could spell the end for the comedy of cruelty|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://telegraph.co.uk./opinion/main.jhtml?xml=/opinion/2008/10/30/dl3001.xml}}</ref>\n\nIn reaction to the telephone calls, Baillie said that her relationship with Brand had been brief and she now felt betrayed that he had revealed it to her grandfather.  Baillie called for both Brand and Ross to be sacked by the BBC and stated that she and her family would be considering whether to make a formal complaint to the police.<ref name=\"Telegraph29Oct08\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Jemima Kiss|date=29 October 2008|title=Sachs' granddaughter calls for Brand and Ross to be sacked|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/29/russell-brand-jonathan-ross1|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited | location=London}}</ref> Sachs stated that he had no intention of making a complaint to the police or taking the matter further.<ref name=\"Apology accepted\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7697988.stm |title=Sachs accepts presenters' apologies|publisher=BBC|date=29 October 2008|accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n===Actions taken by Ross, Brand, and the BBC===\nOn 29 October 2008, [[Director-General of the BBC]] [[Mark Thompson (media executive)|Mark Thompson]] announced that [[Russell Brand]] and [[Jonathan Ross]] were suspended, pending the report of an investigation by [[Tim Davie]], director of BBC audio and music.<ref name=\"suspended\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7696714.stm|title=Brand and Ross suspended by BBC|date=29 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=BBC suspends salamander Davoudi|date=29 October 2008|work=[[Financial Times]]|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/c425fb84-a5b6-11dd-9d26-000077b07658.html}}</ref> The suspension meant that, for the week, Ross would not be appearing on his regular ''[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]'' television show, [[Film... (TV programme)|''Film 2008 with Jonathan Ross'']], or his Saturday-morning [[BBC Radio 2|Radio 2]] show. Similarly Brand would not be hosting his regular Saturday-night Radio 2 show or appearing as a guest captain on an episode of ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'' due to be aired on 30 October; the episode had been taped before his resignation, and aired on BBC Two on 19 January 2011, more than 2 years after the incident.<ref name=\"Telegraph29Oct08\"/> Thompson called the events a \"gross lapse of taste by the performers and the production team\" (who chose to broadcast the advance-recorded show) that angered [[Television licensing in the United Kingdom|licence-payers]].  Thompson offered a personal and unreserved apology to Sachs and his family.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7697354.stm|title=Brand and Ross: BBC statement|last=Thompson|first=Mark|date=29 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref> In an interview, Sachs revealed that he had received and accepted written apologies from Brand and Ross.<ref name=\"Apology accepted\"/> Brand resigned from the BBC later in the day.<ref name=BBCBrandQuits>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7698417.stm|date=29 October 2008|title=Brand quits BBC over prank calls|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nOn the evening of 30 October it was announced that Controller of Radio 2 [[Lesley Douglas]] had tendered her resignation, which had been accepted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7700816.stm|title= Radio 2 boss quits over call row|date=30 October 2008|publisher=BBC}}</ref> Her resignation letter did not address the question of whether Douglas herself had approved the pre-recorded show for transmission.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lesley Douglas profile: Puppet master who shunned the public eye|author=Maggie Brown|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/30/lesleydouglas-bbc|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref> That day, Ross was suspended without pay from all BBC shows for a period of 12 weeks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ross suspended for three months|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7700816.stm|publisher=BBC|date=30 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe BBC issued an apology on 8 November, stating that the telephone calls were \"grossly offensive\" and a \"serious breach of editorial standards\".<ref name=Barber>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5109646.ece|title=David Barber, BBC executive, quits after Brand Ross scandal|work=The Times|author=Nico Hones|date=7 November 2008|accessdate=7 November 2008 | location=London}}</ref> The corporation apologised specifically to Sachs and Baillie, and also to [[Television licence|licence fee payers]]. The evening before this formal apology, David Barber, head of specialist music and compliance at Radio 2, also resigned. Like Douglas,<ref name=Notover>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7703870.stm|title=It's not all over yet|author=Torin Douglas|publisher=BBC News|date=1 November 2008|accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> he had been aware of the contents of the show, and had sanctioned the segment's broadcast.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/3400839/Radio-2-executive-resigns-over-Jonathan-Ross-and-Russell-Brand-prank.html|title=Radio 2 executive resigns over Jonathan Ross and Russell Brand prank|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|author=Anita Singh|date=7 November 2008|accessdate=7 November 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Reactions from politicians and the media===\nFifteen [[Member of Parliament|MP]]s signed a motion in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], tabled by Labour MP [[Andrew MacKinlay]] and Conservative MP [[Nigel Evans]], calling for Brand and Ross to no longer be funded by the [[licence fee#United Kingdom|licence fee]] (which funds the BBC). The chairman of the House of Commons [[Culture, Media and Sport Committee|select committee on culture, media and sport]], [[John Whittingdale]], stated that an investigation by the BBC was needed, but stopped short of calling for Ross and Brand to be sacked.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC should 'take some pain' for phone prank, says Will Wyatt|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Leigh Holmwood|date=28 October 2008|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/28/bbc-russell-brand|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref> The chairman of the [[House of Lords]] Select Committee on Communication, [[Norman Fowler, Baron Fowler|Lord Fowler]], in a letter to The Times (see Fowler in [[#Further reading|Further reading]]) stated that there were fundamental flaws in the way that the BBC was regulated and governed, and that there was \"confusion all round\" because two parallel bodies, the [[BBC Trust]] and Ofcom, were investigating the incident, and it was both unclear which of them the public should complain to and which of them had precedence over the other.<ref name=Times1>{{cite news|title=Russell Brand falls on his sword and a sorry Ross is taken off the air|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|author1=Patrick Foster |author2=Philip Webster |author3=Adam Sherwin |author4=Charlene Sweeney  |last-author-amp=yes |date=30 October 2008|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk./tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5042843.ece}}</ref>\n\nShadow [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport|Culture Secretary]] [[Jeremy Hunt]], speaking on the Radio 4 [[Today Programme]] on 30 October, also refused to say whether he thought Ross should be sacked, asserting that politicians should remain at \"arm's length\" from such decisions. In a speech at the [[London School of Economics]] the previous day he had criticised the decision by the BBC to broadcast the programme, which had been recorded 2 days prior to its transmission, saying that \"[t]he BBC was quite wrong to take the decision to broadcast the offensive phone calls\". He also demurred about calling for the resignations of anyone in BBC management, saying that \"[i]t is wrong, in principle, for politicians to be calling for heads of individual broadcasting to be removed\", and criticised the BBC for not releasing the name of the person who had given the green light for the show to be broadcast.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://walesonline.co.uk./showbiz-and-lifestyle/news/2008/10/30/steve-coogan-speaks-out-about-brand-and-ross-91466-22148936/|title=Steve Coogan speaks out about Brand and Ross|date=30 October 2008|author=Robin Turner|work=[[WalesOnline]]|publisher=Media Wales Ltd}}</ref><ref name=NewStatesman1>{{cite news|title=Tory weighs into Ross/Brand row|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2008/10/ross-brand-bbc-hunt-public|date=29 October 2008|author=Brittany Peats|work=[[New Statesman]]}}</ref>\n\nHunt was speaking to the LSE about socially responsible broadcasting, and stated \"I do think the BBC is a socially responsible broadcaster, I just think we need to hear that.\"  He argued that broadcasters were not being ambitious enough, and outlined his party's plans, should it be elected to government at the next general election, to relax regulation for those broadcasters who agreed to provide only socially responsible output. In addition to citing the Ross/Brand/Sachs affair as a \"perfect example\" of where such a \"responsibility deal\" could have operated, he also pointed to [[Channel 4]] as an example, stating that it was \"not good enough\" for it to produce \"worthy\" programmes such as [[Dispatches (TV series)|''Dispatches'']] documenting alcohol abuse in the US, whilst at the same time it was broadcasting programmes such as ''[[Hollyoaks]]'' where such abuse took up, according to his estimates, 18% of screen time. The culture spokesman for the Liberal Democrats, [[Don Foster, Baron Foster of Bath|Don Foster]], criticised this idea, stating that it threatened the very foundational principles of freedom and independence of British media, arguing that such government interference in television programming would be \"a very sad day for British broadcasting\", and pointing out that regulatory mechanisms already exist to deal with issues such as this.<ref name=NewStatesman1 /><ref>{{cite news|title=Tories mull responsible TV incentives|author=Ian Darby|url=http://brandrepublic.com./News/858123/Tories-mull-responsible-TV-incentives/|date=30 October 2008|publisher=Haymarket Media|work=Brand Republic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Responsibility contract' would threaten media freedom, say Lib Dems|author=Mark Sweney|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 October 2008|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|url=http://guardian.co.uk./politics/2008/oct/29/liberaldemocrats-television}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 October, Conservative MP [[Nadine Dorries]] had already called for the BBC to terminate the contracts of both Ross and Brand, and in the Commons [[David Hanson (politician)|David Hanson]] had criticised the comments for being inappropriate and not \"in keeping with broadcasting\".<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC on defensive and Ofcom steps in as 10,000 complain about Brand and Ross|author=Owen Gibson|date=29 October 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/29/russell-brand-jonathan-ross-bbc}}</ref> The conservative journalist [[Charles Moore (journalist)|Charles Moore]] announced he would not pay his television licence after the BBC's failure to sack Ross,<ref>Charles Moore [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/may/11/charles-moore-fined-tv-licence \"The BBC was too scared to sack Jonathan Ross, so the obscenity goes on\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 22 November 2008</ref> a decision which eventually led to Moore being fined in May 2010.<ref>James Robinson [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/may/11/charles-moore-fined-tv-licence \"Charles Moore fined for Jonathan Ross-inspired TV licence boycott\"], ''The Guardian'', 11 May 2010</ref>\n\nSecretary of State for Justice [[Jack Straw]], writing in his local newspaper the ''[[Lancashire Telegraph]]'' on 30 October (see Straw in [[#Further reading|Further reading]]), became the first Cabinet Minister to call for the pair to be sacked, arguing that if both presenters had worked in [[Independent Local Radio|local radio]] \"they'd have been given their [[P45 (tax)|P45]] before you could say 'Jack Robinson'.\"<ref name=Times1 /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blackburncitizen.co.uk/news/3801342.Sack_Jonathan_Ross__say_East_Lancashire_MPs/|date=30 October 2008|title=Sack Jonathan Ross, say East Lancashire MPs Jack Straw and Nigel Evans|work=[[The Citizen (Blackburn)|The Citizen]]|location=Blackburn|publisher=Newsquest Media Group}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, Shadow Leader of the House of Commons and future Prime Minister, [[Theresa May]], called for a Commons debate on the BBC's handling of the affair.<ref>{{cite news|title=New exit in Russell Brand row as Jonathan Ross suspended unpaid|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk./tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5050293.ece|author1=Nico Hines  |author2=Philippe Naughton |lastauthoramp=yes |work=[[The Times]]|location=London|publisher=News International Limited}}</ref>\n\n===Reaction against censures and suspensions===\nIn the days following the suspensions, a number of celebrities, particularly from television and radio, came out in support of Brand and Ross. Many felt that, whilst the incident was unacceptable, it was not deserving of the strong criticism it received, especially when there were other issues troubling the United Kingdom.\n\nRod McKenzie, the editor of BBC Radio 1 ''[[Newsbeat]]'', observed on the BBC Editors' weblog (see [[#Further reading|Further reading]]) that audience reactions to Brand's and Ross' remarks had been polarised, noting that whilst his colleagues at [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]], [[BBC Radio 5 Live|Radio 5 Live]], television, and the [[BBC World Service]] had been seeing one thing, the younger audiences of Radio 1 had been reacting quite differently, and were broadly supportive of Ross and Brand. Some were amazed at the comments of the Prime Minister, with one person observing that \"[t]he financial markets are wrecked and all he can do is talk about a petty joke.\"  Others stated that people should \"calm down\", \"get a grip\", and that the subject had been \"blown out of all proportion\". McKenzie also characterised the reaction from the news media as containing \"anger: some genuine, some of it synthetic. Some of it comes from the BBC's usual critics.\"  He stated that for the people who worked in the media \"profile and salary-envy and [[:wikt:schadenfreude|schadenfreude]] may play a part in all this. But how many heard the original transmission and how many are responding to the newspapers' quotes or others' arguments?\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Criticism of Russell Brand and Jonathan Ross driven by 'salary envy', says BBC executive|author=Nicole Martin|date=29 October 2008|url=http://telegraph.co.uk./news/newstopics/celebritynews/3280037/Criticism-of-Russell-Brand-and-Jonathan-Ross-driven-by-salary-envy-says-BBC-executive.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Tim Shaw (presenter)|Tim Shaw]], disc jockey for [[Absolute Radio]], also supported Ross and Brand, appearing on BBC News wearing a T-shirt that read \"I back Brand.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com./International/Story?id=6139816&page=2|publisher=[[ABC News]]|title=BBC Comedians' Joke Falls Flat|author=Gabrial O'Rorke|date=29 October 2008}}</ref> The television presenter [[Paul O'Grady]] stated that the comedians' behaviour was \"well out of order\". However, he also suggested that the Prime Minister should get on with more important matters than complaining about media gossip.<ref>{{cite news|title= O'Grady: 'Move on from Ross and Brand'|date=30 October 2008|author=David Balls|work=[[DigitalSpy]]|url=http://digitalspy.co.uk./showbiz/a134098/ogrady-move-on-from-ross-and-brand.html}}</ref> [[Carol McGiffin]], a presenter on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s [[Daytime television|daytime]] programme ''[[Loose Women]]'' similarly supported the pair, criticising those who complained and stating that she could not wait to download the official [[podcast]] which included the incident.<ref>{{cite episode |title=[[Loose Women]] |network=[[ITV1]] |airdate=27 October 2008 |minutes=60 }}</ref>\n\n[[Noel Gallagher]] of the group [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]], a friend of Brand's, complained that the press had \"dictated the tone\" of the controversy, and thought it \"typical of the English in general\" when \"10,000 people get outraged, but only days after it has happened\". Gallagher claimed to have spoken to Brand, who told Gallagher he was \"going to fall on his sword\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Oasis' Noel Gallagher 'outraged' at Russell Brand BBC scandal|work=[[NME]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://www.nme.com/news/oasis/40735}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC|date=30 October 2008|title=Oasis star backs radio pal Brand|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7699623.stm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[Digital Spy]]|title=Gallagher 'outraged' by Brand resignation|author=Alex Fletcher|url=http://digitalspy.co.uk./showbiz/a134117/gallagher-outraged-by-brand-resignation.html?id=134117&id=134117|publisher=Digital Spy Limited|date=30 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nA petition on the GoPetition web site, calling for the BBC \"to turn blame on the '[[Andrew Sachs]]' incident away from [[Russell Brand]] and [[Jonathan Ross]], and instead onto whoever green lighted the show\" had garnered a mere 336 signatures by 29 October. At the same time, a similar group on Facebook had over 1,000 members.<ref>{{cite news|title=Petition supports Brand and Ross|date=29 October 2008|work=[[Web User]]|url=http://webuser.co.uk./news/news.php?id=270991}}</ref>  By 30 October, the petition had risen to 4,000 signatures and the Facebook group to 15,609 members.<ref name=Conlan1>{{cite news|title=Brand-Ross Facebook supporters to protest outside Daily Mail|author=Tara Conlan|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/31/facebook-jonathan-ross|date=31 October 2008}}</ref> By 2 November, the Facebook group had over 30,000 members,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/entertainment/No-laughing-matter-as-.4652344.jp|title=Have you heard the one about the gagged comedians?|last=Horne|first=Marc|date=2 November 2008|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=2 November 2008|location=Edinburgh}}</ref> which had risen to over 43,000 members by 5 November.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dancer in Sachs prank criticises BBC response|author=Owen Gibson|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=6 November 2008|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/nov/06/bbc-ross-brand-georgina-baillie}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October, fans of Ross and Brand protested outside of the offices of the BBC. On 31 October, fans prepared to hold a protest outside of the offices of the ''Daily Mail'' and of the BBC.<ref name=Conlan1 />\n\nComedian [[Jimmy Carr]] also expressed his support for Ross, saying the issue had been blown out of proportion, and blamed the media themselves for escalating it further, stating that Ross was a \"national treasure\".<ref>{{cite news | title=Ross pulls out of Comedy Awards | date=31 October 2008 | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7702309.stm | publisher =BBC News | accessdate = 31 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nFormer celebrity publicist [[Max Clifford]] played down the apparent outrage aimed at Brand. In an interview he said \"I don't think this will cause any problems for Russell Brand. He's known to be controversial and, if anything, it will make him more popular amongst his fans, who will have thought this was hilarious...They won't see anything wrong in what he did. It is a big PR success for him...He will have no problem with his career.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3288422/Russell-Brand-controversy-will-only-increase-his-popularity-experts-say.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|author=Anita Singh|date=31 October 2008|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|title=Russell Brand controversy will only increase his popularity, experts say | location=London}}</ref>\n\nTV critic and columnist [[Charlie Brooker]] stated on his show, ''[[Charlie Brooker's Screenwipe]]'', his worry that the controversy would lead to a [[Chilling effect (term)|chilling effect]] on comedy, and that the BBC and others would self-censor too much in future. He went on to say that the attitude displayed by the complainants and the BBC's backing down would have, in earlier times, precluded the production of much of what was at the time edgy comedy and made culture poorer for it (citing ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'', ''[[The Day Today]]'' and ''[[The Young Ones (TV series)|The Young Ones]]'' amongst others as shows that would have not been commissioned owing to their controversial content). While pouring scorn on those who had complained without seeing the programme, and attacking newspapers that attempted to stir up further controversy (in particular the ''[[Daily Mail]]''), he did not appear to defend Brand and Ross in particular, stating that the possibility of people being offended by some misjudged humour is \"the price you pay for freedom of speech.\" In a further column in ''[[The Guardian]]'', he reiterated this point as well as saying that \"people who retrospectively complain to Ofcom about material they've only read about second-hand are, in essence, a bunch of sanctimonious crybabies indulging in a wretched form of masturbation.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Charlie Brooker's screen burn|date=29 November 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2008/nov/29/charlie-brooker-screen-burn-tv | location=London | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC website\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7698477.stm|title= Prank row: Georgina Baillie's reaction|date=29 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=7 November 2008}}</ref><ref name ='publicityparadox'>{{cite news|author=Matthew Taylor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/30/russell-brand-ross-baillie-sachs |title=Georgina Baillie: the Satanic Slut at the centre of the Ross-Brand controversy |work=The Guardian |date= 30 October 2008|accessdate=22 August 2010 | location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"BroadcastFiveTV\">{{cite news|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/2008/10/five_to_air_doc_on_russell_and_ross.html|title=Five to air doc on Russell and Ross|work=Broadcast|date=31 October 2008|accessdate =2 November 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7710341.stm|title=Radio 2 row 'out of proportion'|publisher=BBC News|date=7 November 2008|accessdate =7 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Reaction from Georgina Baillie===\n\n====Interviews====\nReacting to the suspension of [[Russell Brand]] and [[Jonathan Ross]] on 29 October, Baillie remarked: \"I'm thrilled because justice has been done...It's despicable. Calling me that in public, not only does it damage my relationship with my granddad but it could permanently damage my life as well,\" despite having declared apathy to the sentiment referenced in the latter sentence on her Myspace page.<ref name=\"BBC website\"/><ref name=\"publicityparadox\"/>\n\nA week later, on 5 November 2008, UK television channel [[Five (TV channel)|Five]] broadcast an hour-length documentary on the incident, titled ''Russell & Ross: What the F*** Was All That About?'' featuring an exclusive interview with Baillie.<ref name=\"BroadcastFiveTV\"/> Baillie stated in the interview that \"I think it's way out of proportion what's happened and I don't hate either of them \u2013 I don't at all\", going on to say \"I think they're really talented comedians and I think a world without [[Jonathan Ross]] and [[Russell Brand]] would be a very sad, dull place.\" She concluded by saying that Brand needed to learn about respecting women, while Ross should just think before he speaks, \"I don't have any harder feeling than that.\"<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Baillie also made clear that she would not object to the reinstatement of both Brand and Ross.<ref name=Barber/>\n\nOn 14 May 2009, Baillie was a guest on the BBC politics and current affairs programme ''[[This Week (BBC One TV series)|This Week]]''. She was questioned by host [[Andrew Neil]] and regular guests [[Michael Portillo]] and [[Diane Abbott]] about the Brand row within discussion of the general subject of the present day worth and genuineness of public figures saying sorry, in the wake of public apologies from members of parliament (MP's) and Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] following the events of the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|MP's expenses row]]. Asked by Neil if receiving an apology from Brand and Ross had mattered to her, she said yes, as she had been \"publicly offended and humiliated\", and her grandfather \"had been humiliated too\". When asked by Abbott if all the publicity surrounding the Brand row had helped her career, she responded \"not necessarily ... one would think so, but not really.\" Neil further asked if the apology she received had helped, she replied yes, stating \"definitely\" to the follow-up comment from Neil of \"better to get it than not get it?\" When asked finally on the row by Neil if she thought the apologies from Brand and Ross were genuine, she replied that she thought Ross' was, but the fact that Brand had joked about the row on his later tour negated his apology.\n\n{{section move from|date=January 2020}}\n====Songwriting====\nIn 2010, Baillie teamed up with singer [[Adam Ant]] (whose drummer Hayley Leggs had been a member, alongside Baillie, of [[burlesque]] troupe The Satanic Sluts) to compose the song Gun in Your Pocket, about Ross, Brand and the entire affair, which he intended to release as the lead single for his ninth album ''[[Adam Ant Is the Blueblack Hussar in Marrying the Gunner's Daughter]]'' (with a rerecording of early 1980s outtake Who's A Goofy Bunny Then? as the B-side in tribute to the recently deceased [[Malcolm McLaren]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/04165-adam-ant-interview-oasis-lady-gaga-madonna-punk |title=Features &#124; A Wild Nobility: An Adam Ant Exclusive By Simon Price |publisher=The Quietus |accessdate=22 August 2010}}</ref> The project was put on hold when Ant (who has a history of [[bipolar disorder]] and was widely suspected around this time to have been undergoing a fresh [[Bipolar disorder#Manic episodes|manic]] episode)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.holymoly.com/celebrity-news/adam-ants-comeback-all-delusion45650 |title=Adam Ant's comeback \"all delusion\" &#124; Celebrity News |publisher=Holy Moly! |date=21 April 2010 |accessdate=22 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712214236/http://www.holymoly.com/celebrity-news/adam-ants-comeback-all-delusion45650 |archivedate=12 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> was once again [[involuntary commitment|sectioned]] on 18 May 2010 However he soon resumed his comeback and Gun in Your Pocket was finally released in October 2012 as the B-side to Cool Zombie, the eventual first single from the album (which finally emerged in January 2013).  \n\nBaillie and Ant composed a second track about the Ross-Brand affair, Rubber Medusa, a song focussed mainly on Brand and written from Baillie's perspective.  Baillie's band, the [[Fiona Bevan#Poussez Posse|Poussez Posse]], performed this second song regularly in live support slots for Ant's UK, mainland European and Australian tours during 2011\u20132012.  Commenting on the two songs in an interview by [[John Robb (musician)|John Robb]], Baillie noted \"The first one that Adam and I wrote was about an ex of mine- guess who! Which is not on the album, which is called Gun in Your Pocket ...(Subsequently) the first one Adam and I wrote together was Rubber Medusa, which was about Russell, Adam came up with the title which is a quote from the [[Jubilee (1978 film)|Jubilee]] film, [Brand] does look like a rubber [[Medusa]] so I see why he said it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://louderthanwar.com/25352/|title=Georgie Girl and her Poussez Posse : interview|work=Louder Than War}}</ref>\n\n===Support for Lesley Douglas===\nA number of radio personalities employed by the BBC came out in support of [[Lesley Douglas]], after her resignation. Douglas was aware of the contents of the programme, but had not heard them before they were broadcast. She sanctioned its broadcast with a single word e-mail of \"Yes\" sent from her [[BlackBerry]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/nov/25/lesleydouglas-bbc | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Lesley Douglas to join Universal Music | first=John | last=Plunkett | date=25 November 2008 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> Amongst her supporters were [[Chris Evans (presenter)|Chris Evans]] and [[Terry Wogan]], both of whom worked for BBC Radio 2 at the time, and Dame [[Liz Forgan]], who called her one of the \"outstanding broadcasters of her generation\", and said that the BBC had \"lost its wits\". Mark Thompson said that because of her knowledge of the broadcast, she had to shoulder some of the responsibility.<ref name=Notover/>\n\n===Subsequent appearances by Brand and Ross===\nRoss had been scheduled to host the 2008 [[British Comedy Awards]] for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] during the period of his suspension from the BBC; however, on 31 October he stepped down.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ross steps down from awards show|work=[[Shropshire Star]]|url=http://shropshirestar.com./2008/10/31/bbc-suspends-jonathan-ross/|date=31 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Tara Conlan|title=Jonathan Ross pulls out of hosting British Comedy Awards|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/31/jonathan-ross-itv|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher='Guardian News and Media Limited|date=31 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 October, Brand left the country, saying that he had work to do in America, including TV programmes and film collaborations with [[Judd Apatow]] and [[Helen Mirren]].<ref name=Notover/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7703014.stm|title=Brand to film with Helen Mirren|publisher=BBC News|date=1 November 2008|accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> The second series of Brand's [[Channel 4]] television show ''[[Russell Brand's Ponderland]]'' aired as normal on the previous evening, attracting 1 million viewers, the show's largest ever audience. A further 180,000 watched the show time-shifted on the Channel 4+1 [[timeshift channel]]. The first series of ''Ponderland'', aired in October 2007, had been watched by 840,000 viewers, including those watching Channel 4+1. The channel reported that it had received 164 complaints from the public, many of these criticising the decision to broadcast the programme, rather than a reflection on the content, and the majority before the programme was transmitted; the show also attracted 212 emails and phone-calls of praise from fans and as such was the most praised programme screened on [[Channel 4]] for that month.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brand praised for Ponderland|publisher=broadcastnow.co.uk|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/2008/11/brand_praised_for_ponderland.html|date=5 November 2008}}</ref><ref name=Holmwood1>{{cite news|title=TV ratings: Russell Brand's post-Sachsgate TV debut bags 1m viewers|author=Leigh Holmwood|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=31 October 2008|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/31/tvratings-russell-brand}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://digitalspy.co.uk./tv/a134243/brands-ponderland-draws-1m.html|title=Brand's 'Ponderland' draws 1m|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=31 October 2008|author=Neil Wilkes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Channel 4 viewers unfazed by Brand|url=http://www.metro.co.uk./fame/article.html?Channel_4_viewers_unfazed_by_Brand&in_article_id=382486|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|date=31 October 2008|publisher=Associated Newspapers Limited}}</ref>\n\nBrand similarly continued to be on the front cover of [[PETA]]'s \"Vegetarian Starter Kit\" booklet, despite people protesting to the organisation. PETA's director, Robbie LeBlanc, said that Brand, who had previously won PETA's Sexiest Vegetarian Celebrity contest twice, would remain on the cover \"because Mr Sachs, who is also a PETA supporter, has accepted Mr Brand's apology, and that's good enough for us.\"<ref>{{cite news|title= Russell Brand Wins Support of PETA Over BBC Prank Scandal|author=Jason Gregory|work=[[Gigwise]]|url=http://gigwise.com./news/47193/Russell-Brand-Wins-Support-Of-PETA-Over-BBC-Prank-Scandal|date=31 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nme.com./news/russell-brand/40766|title=PETA to stand by Russell Brand despite BBC ban|work=[[NME]]|date=31 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nBrand went on to win the British Comedy Award for Best Live Standup Performer. In his acceptance speech, Brand dedicated his award to Ross.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brand wins British Comedy Award|publisher=BBC|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7769652.stm|date=7 December 2008|accessdate =1 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter being taken off the air due to Ross' suspension, ''[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]'' returned to [[BBC One]] on 23 January 2009, featuring guests [[Tom Cruise]], [[Lee Evans (comedian)|Lee Evans]] and [[Stephen Fry]]. The show was watched by 5.1 million viewers, an increase from the 3.74 million of the last show before going off air. Ross' return attracted 25 complaints and 3 messages of support to the BBC.<ref name=\"BBC24Jan09\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7849582.stm |title=Ross TV return is watched by 5.1m |date=24 January 2009 |accessdate=27 January 2009 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, ''[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]'' was nominated for a BAFTA. According to ''[[The Times]]'', Ross was nominated soon after he was banned.<ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Patrick|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5971275.ece|title=BBC banned offensive Ross, then put him up for a Bafta|work=The Times|date=25 March 2009|accessdate=26 March 2009 | location=London}}</ref> Melody Sachs complained about Ross being nominated so soon after the controversy in an interview with ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', saying: \"I am amazed that Ross should get rewarded with a mouth like his. Nobody is saying he hasn't got talent, but what he did was so disgusting. Of course he is not worth the money, but he is good at his job. However, I don't think he should be rewarded so soon after what happened. It is like people are saying, 'Let's forget all about it and see what we can give him.' It is wrong and bad timing to give or even put up this guy for recognition when he has done such a terrible thing. It was unforgivable, really. I'm not angry, I just don't believe it.\"<ref name=\"DT BAFTA\">{{cite news|last=Singh|first=Anita|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/5043185/Baftas-family-of-Andrew-Sachs-flabbergasted-by-Jonathan-Ross-nomination.html|title=Baftas: family of Andrew Sachs 'flabbergasted' by Jonathan Ross nomination|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=24 March 2009|accessdate=24 March 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nSachs himself said that the nomination was: \"a bit of a surprise\", and that: \"One would question the reasons when it comes so quickly after what happened. I wonder how much it has to do with trying to comfort him. I don't know. That is how it happens. That is showbusiness.\"<ref name=\"DT BAFTA\"/>\n\n==BBC Trust ruling==\nOn 21 November 2008, the BBC's watchdog [[BBC Trust]] said that the phone calls were a \"deplorable intrusion with no editorial justification.\"<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationDeplorable\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=Jonathan Ross and Russell Brand's lewd calls to actor Andrew Sachs were a \"deplorable intrusion with no editorial justification\", the BBC Trust has said.}}</ref> The Trust found that the existing BBC guidelines should have been sufficient to have prevented the incident, and that the \"very offensive\" programme should \"never have been recorded.\"<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationFailures\"/> It found the failures lay in mistakes made by BBC editorial and compliance management.<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationFailures\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=Referring to the incident, BBC trustee Richard Tait said three main failures were made \u2013 in exercising editorial control; in following established compliance systems and a failure of judgment in taking editorial decisions. He said the furore could have been avoided if BBC management had followed the corporation's editorial guidelines. \"It is a catalogue of editorial and management failures,\" he added. \"It was a very offensive programme which should never have been recorded. Once the offensive phone call was made, the recording should have stopped and senior management alerted,\" he said. }}</ref> The Trust gave its backing to the BBC's response to the incident and Ross' 12-week suspension.<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationBBCActions\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=However, he said the trust considered the BBC's response to the controversy to have been appropriate. Asked if any further action would be taken against Jonathan Ross, Sir Michael said: \"We are very clear that the director general has taken the right action with respect to Jonathan Ross.\"}}</ref>\n\nEchoing the findings of the BBC Trust, the BBC itself stated the incident was a \"very, very serious failure in a radio programme where editorial judgement was exercised that seriously let the BBC down.\"<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationDeplorableBBCResponse\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=The BBC said in a statement \"It was a very, very serious failure in a radio programme where editorial judgement was exercised that seriously let the BBC down,\"\n}}</ref>\n\nThe Trust also criticised Brand's \"so-called apology\" of 25 October, and the staff of [[Chris Moyles]]' BBC Radio 1 show for also breaching BBC guidelines for comments by Brand in an interview on the morning of 21 October at a time when children were likely to be listening.<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationDeplorableBrandActions\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=Mr Tait said the offence of the original broadcast was compounded by Russell Brand's appearance on Chris Moyles' Radio 1 show on 21 October. He said this discussion, in itself, was also in breach of editorial guidelines in respect of privacy, offence and the fact it was broadcast at a time when children were likely to be listening. Mr Tait added that the trust considered Brand's \"unacceptable, so-called apology\" broadcast on Radio 2 on 25 October \"exacerbated the intrusion into privacy and the offence\". The trust ... recommended ... that there should be tighter controls on shows made by companies owned by their performers. Brand's show was made by his own firm.}}</ref> The Trust recommended tighter controls for programmes such as Brand's, made by companies owned by their performers.<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationDeplorableBrandActions\"/> Long-term effects of the controversy would include the setting up of a register of high-risk programmes.<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationDeplorableRiskResgister\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=Steps taken to ensure there is no repeat of the incident include creating a register of high-risk programmes.}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5023135.ece|title=Transcript: 'offensive' Brand and Ross calls|work=[[The Times]]|date=27 October 2008 | location=London | accessdate=23 May 2010 |first1=Charles |last1=Bremner |first2=David |last2=Robertson}}\n* {{cite news|title=Jonathan Ross and Russell Brand: past controversies|author=Nicole Martin|date=29 October 2008|url=http://telegraph.co.uk./news/3280359/Jonathan-Ross-and-Russell-Brand-past-controversies.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}\n* {{cite news|title=Ross and Brand, the bigger picture|author=Lord Fowler|authorlink=Norman Fowler|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=30 October 2008|url=http://timesonline.co.uk./tol/comment/letters/article5040972.ece}}\n* {{cite news|author=Jack Straw|authorlink=Jack Straw|title=The issues over standards at the BBC|work=[[Lancashire Telegraph]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/comment/3804407.The_issues_over_standards_at_the_BBC/|publisher=Newsquest Media Group}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk./blogs/theeditors/2008/10/open_and_shut_case.html |author= Rod McKenzie |publisher= BBC |title= Open and shut case? |date= 29 October 2008 |accessdate= 29 October 2008}}\n*{{cite web |title= And if Russell Brand and Jonathan Ross had been newspaper journalists? |website= journalism.co.uk |date= 30 October 2008 |url= http://www.journalism.co.uk/6/articles/532679.php |accessdate= 30 October 2008 |author= Martin Moore |publisher= Mousetrap Media Ltd}}\n* {{cite news |author=Mark Lawson|work=[[The Guardian]] |title= Welcome to the Blander Broadcasting Corporation |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |date=30 October 2008 |url=http://guardian.co.uk./commentisfree/2008/oct/30/bbc-jonathan-ross-russell-brand}}\n* {{cite news |author= India Knight |work= [[The Times]] |url= http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/india_knight/article5062837.ece?Submitted=true |title= Pity the women who come within range of Brand and Ross |location= London |date= 2 November 2008 | accessdate= 23 May 2010|author-link= India Knight }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/03_04_09_russelbrand.pdf Ofcom ruling on the incident]\n\n{{Russell Brand}}\n{{BBC Radio 2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russell Brand Show prank telephone calls row, The}}\n[[Category:2008 in radio]]\n[[Category:2008 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:BBC controversies]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 2]]\n[[Category:Entertainment scandals]]\n[[Category:Prank calling]]\n[[Category:Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]\n[[Category:Radio controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:''The Russell Brand Show'' prank telephone calls row}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right;margin-left:1em;text-align:center;\"\n|-\n| style=\"width:33%;\"| [[Image:Russell Brand Arthur Premier.jpg|110px]]\n| style=\"width:33%;\"| [[Image:JonathanRoss.jpg|110px]]\n| style=\"width:33%;\"| [[Image:Andrew sachs.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n! <small>[[Russell Brand]]</small>\n! <small>[[Jonathan Ross]]</small>\n! <small>[[Andrew Sachs]]</small>\n|}\nIn an episode of [[BBC Radio 2|BBC Radio 2's]] ''[[The Russell Brand Show (radio show)|The Russell Brand Show]]'' broadcast on Saturday 18 October 2008, comedian [[Russell Brand]] and presenter [[Jonathan Ross]] made [[prank call]]s to actor [[Andrew Sachs]] that led to controversy in the United Kingdom. Brand and Ross called Sachs to interview him on-air; when he did not answer, they left a series of lewd messages on his answering machine, including comments about Brand's relationship with Sachs' granddaughter, Georgina Baillie. After initially receiving little attention, a 26 October article in ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' led to widespread criticism of Brand, Ross and the editorial decisions of the [[BBC]], with the event becoming known as \"'''Sachsgate'''\" or \"'''Manuelgate'''\" (a reference to Sachs' [[Manuel (Fawlty Towers)|character]] in ''[[Fawlty Towers]]'').<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/sachsgate-obscene-prank-calls-russell-9376380|title=Andrew Sachs was 'haunted' by obscene calls from Russell Brand and Jonathan Ross|last=Rutter|first=Claire|date=2016-12-02|work=mirror|access-date=2017-08-12}}</ref>\n\nBrand and Ross were criticised by a number of [[Members of Parliament]], including [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]], and the BBC received a record number of complaints. The BBC suspended Ross while it and [[Ofcom]] launched investigations. Both Brand and Radio 2 controller [[Lesley Douglas]] resigned from the BBC. On 30 October, the BBC suspended Ross without pay for 12 weeks. The BBC was fined \u00a3150,000 by Ofcom.<ref>{{cite news|last=Holmwood|first=Leigh|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2009/apr/03/russell-brand-jonathan-ross-bbc-fine|title=BBC fined \u00a3150,000 over Russell Brand and Jonathan Ross phone prank scandal|work=The Guardian|accessdate=3 April 2009|location=London, UK}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nFrom April 2006 through to October 2008, [[Russell Brand]] presented the weekly BBC radio show [[The Russell Brand Show (radio show)|''The Russell Brand Show'']]. In most episodes Brand was joined by his co-host [[Matt Morgan (comedian)|Matt Morgan]] who would often steer him in certain directions regarding what to talk about. Brand sometimes called in a variety of his celebrity friends as well, including [[Noel Fielding]], [[Jonah Hill]] and [[Morrissey]], to talk on the show each week.\n\nOn 11 October 2008, [[David Baddiel]] co-hosted Brand's show. Baddiel recalled having met Georgina Baillie at Brand's home and being told that her grandfather was actor [[Andrew Sachs]]. According to Baddiel, Baillie said \"Don't tell him I was here!\"<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC apologises for lewd phone calls by Russell Brand and Jonathan Ross|date=28 October 2008|work=[[The Times]]|author=Patrick Foster|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5022840.ece | location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Prank calls==\n\nOn Thursday 16 October 2008, Sachs, who famously portrayed [[Manuel (Fawlty Towers)|Manuel]] in television comedy ''[[Fawlty Towers]]'', was scheduled to be a phone-in guest on Brand's evening radio show.  The show was to be pre-recorded due to Brand's work commitments.<ref name=\"bbcApology\"/>\n\nAfter being unable to reach Sachs on his home telephone, Brand and his co-host of the week, fellow Radio 2 DJ [[Jonathan Ross]], left Sachs four voice messages. In the first message, Brand joked about ''Fawlty Towers'' and the fact that both he and Sachs had appeared in ''[[The Bill]]'', but was interrupted by Ross shouting out \"he fucked your granddaughter\". The rest of the message and the following three messages were all characterised by Brand and Ross attempting to apologise for Ross' outburst, but each quickly descended into farce, with, for example, Brand singing to Sachs: \"It was consensual and she wasn't menstrual\" and Ross asking to marry him.<ref name=\"bbcApology\"/>  Brand later said that listening to those calls is like hearing \"two idiots dancing towards a canyon\"; however no complaints were received.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/4289499/Russell-Brand-jokes-about-Andrew-Sachs-scandal-in-new-comedy-gig.html |title=Russell Brand jokes about Andrew Sachs scandal in new comedy gig |work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London |first=Aislinn |last=Simpson |date=19 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Complaints==\nOn 25 October, Brand presented his last edition of his radio show with co-host [[Simon Amstell]], which they performed live. Shortly before going on air, Brand was informed that ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' would be running a story about the phone calls. During the show, Brand apologised to Sachs, but also devoted much of the show to deriding the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' for its support of [[Nazism]] in the run up to [[World War II]]. Even in his apology to Sachs, Brand stated \"what's worse \u2013 leaving a swearword on [[Andrew Sachs]]' answerphone or tacitly supporting [[Adolf Hitler]] when he took charge of the [[Third Reich]]?\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/27/russell-brand-daily-mail-fawlty-towers |title=Russell Brand highlights Mail Hitler links in apology to Fawlty Towers star |date=27 October 2008 |work=The Guardian |location=London |first=John |last=Plunkett}}</ref>\n\nThe incident escalated into a media and political storm that, in much of the British media, eclipsed news of the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|global financial crisis]], the [[2008 United States presidential election|US Presidential election]], and [[2008 Nord-Kivu fighting|fighting in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]].<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC suspends top stars in media storm|date=29 October 2008|agency=[[Agence France-Presse]]|url=http://currentaffairs.ninemsn.com.au./article.aspx?id=657414}}</ref>\n\nSachs later stated he had not given permission for the messages to be broadcast.<ref name=\"Telegraph29Oct08\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/3278635/Jonathan-Ross-and-Russell-Brand-suspended-by-BBC-over-Andrew-Sachs-calls.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|title=Jonathan Ross and Russell Brand suspended by BBC over Andrew Sachs calls|date=29 October 2008|accessdate=29 October 2008|author=Anita Singh | location=London}}</ref> The BBC originally stated that they were \"not aware of any complaint by Mr Sachs\", but later confirmed a complaint had been received, and apologised.<ref name=\"bbcApology\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7692911.stm|title=BBC apologises over Brand prank|date=27 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=27 October 2008}}</ref> Brand issued an apology for making the calls<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7691641.stm|title=Brand 'sorry' for telephone stunt|publisher=BBC|date=26 October 2008}}</ref> but stated it was \"funny\" during his last radio show, before the ''Mail'' had printed the story.<ref name=\"bbcApology\" /> [[Ofcom]], the telecommunications regulator, announced its own investigation.<ref>{{cite news|author=Rob Shepherd|title= Pressure mounts over Ross and Brand phone prank|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/2008/10/pressure_mounts_over_ross_and_brand_phone_prank.html|work= [[Broadcast Now]]|date=28 October 2008|accessdate=28 October 2008}}</ref> On 28 October 2008, the BBC said that it had received 4,700 complaints,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7694921.stm|title=Ofcom to launch BBC Brand inquiry|date=28 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 October 2008}}</ref> after the calls became international news.<ref name=\"NME29Oct08\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/the-killers/40721|title=Killers and Glasvegas caught-up in Jonathan Ross and Russell Brand's BBC ban|date=29 October 2008|work=[[NME]]|accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref><ref name=Times2 /> Later the same day, this number had passed 10,000.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7694989.stm|title=Timeline: Russell Brand prank calls|publisher=BBC|date=30 October 2008}}</ref> The same afternoon, [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Gordon Brown]] called the incident \"clearly inappropriate and unacceptable\".<ref name=\"sack\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7696714.stm|title=BBC pressured to sack presenters|date=29 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref> The following day the number of complaints was said to have topped 18,000.<ref name=\"timeline\"/>\n\nThis incident resulted in the second-highest number of complaints to the BBC in recent years, second only to its airing of ''[[Jerry Springer: The Opera]]''.<ref name=Times2>{{cite news|title=Tories demand Commons debate on BBC 'Manuelgate'|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=30 October 2008|author=Philippe Naughton|url=http://timesonline.co.uk./tol/news/uk/article5047594.ece|publisher=News International Limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Offence record: The most complained-about shows|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 October 2008|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/29/russell-brand-jonathan-ross-complaints|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=This could spell the end for the comedy of cruelty|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://telegraph.co.uk./opinion/main.jhtml?xml=/opinion/2008/10/30/dl3001.xml}}</ref>\n\nIn reaction to the telephone calls, Baillie said that her relationship with Brand had been brief and she now felt betrayed that he had revealed it to her grandfather.  Baillie called for both Brand and Ross to be sacked by the BBC and stated that she and her family would be considering whether to make a formal complaint to the police.<ref name=\"Telegraph29Oct08\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Jemima Kiss|date=29 October 2008|title=Sachs' granddaughter calls for Brand and Ross to be sacked|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/29/russell-brand-jonathan-ross1|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited | location=London}}</ref> Sachs stated that he had no intention of making a complaint to the police or taking the matter further.<ref name=\"Apology accepted\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7697988.stm |title=Sachs accepts presenters' apologies|publisher=BBC|date=29 October 2008|accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n===Actions taken by Ross, Brand, and the BBC===\nOn 29 October 2008, [[Director-General of the BBC]] [[Mark Thompson (media executive)|Mark Thompson]] announced that [[Russell Brand]] and [[Jonathan Ross]] were suspended, pending the report of an investigation by [[Tim Davie]], director of BBC audio and music.<ref name=\"suspended\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7696714.stm|title=Brand and Ross suspended by BBC|date=29 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=BBC suspends salamander Davoudi|date=29 October 2008|work=[[Financial Times]]|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/c425fb84-a5b6-11dd-9d26-000077b07658.html}}</ref> The suspension meant that, for the week, Ross would not be appearing on his regular ''[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]'' television show, [[Film... (TV programme)|''Film 2008 with Jonathan Ross'']], or his Saturday-morning [[BBC Radio 2|Radio 2]] show. Similarly Brand would not be hosting his regular Saturday-night Radio 2 show or appearing as a guest captain on an episode of ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'' due to be aired on 30 October; the episode had been taped before his resignation, and aired on BBC Two on 19 January 2011, more than 2 years after the incident.<ref name=\"Telegraph29Oct08\"/> Thompson called the events a \"gross lapse of taste by the performers and the production team\" (who chose to broadcast the advance-recorded show) that angered [[Television licensing in the United Kingdom|licence-payers]].  Thompson offered a personal and unreserved apology to Sachs and his family.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7697354.stm|title=Brand and Ross: BBC statement|last=Thompson|first=Mark|date=29 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 October 2008}}</ref> In an interview, Sachs revealed that he had received and accepted written apologies from Brand and Ross.<ref name=\"Apology accepted\"/> Brand resigned from the BBC later in the day.<ref name=BBCBrandQuits>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7698417.stm|date=29 October 2008|title=Brand quits BBC over prank calls|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nOn the evening of 30 October it was announced that Controller of Radio 2 [[Lesley Douglas]] had tendered her resignation, which had been accepted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7700816.stm|title= Radio 2 boss quits over call row|date=30 October 2008|publisher=BBC}}</ref> Her resignation letter did not address the question of whether Douglas herself had approved the pre-recorded show for transmission.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lesley Douglas profile: Puppet master who shunned the public eye|author=Maggie Brown|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/30/lesleydouglas-bbc|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref> That day, Ross was suspended without pay from all BBC shows for a period of 12 weeks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ross suspended for three months|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7700816.stm|publisher=BBC|date=30 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe BBC issued an apology on 8 November, stating that the telephone calls were \"grossly offensive\" and a \"serious breach of editorial standards\".<ref name=Barber>{{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5109646.ece|title=David Barber, BBC executive, quits after Brand Ross scandal|work=The Times|author=Nico Hones|date=7 November 2008|accessdate=7 November 2008 | location=London}}</ref> The corporation apologised specifically to Sachs and Baillie, and also to [[Television licence|licence fee payers]]. The evening before this formal apology, David Barber, head of specialist music and compliance at Radio 2, also resigned. Like Douglas,<ref name=Notover>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7703870.stm|title=It's not all over yet|author=Torin Douglas|publisher=BBC News|date=1 November 2008|accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> he had been aware of the contents of the show, and had sanctioned the segment's broadcast.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/3400839/Radio-2-executive-resigns-over-Jonathan-Ross-and-Russell-Brand-prank.html|title=Radio 2 executive resigns over Jonathan Ross and Russell Brand prank|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|author=Anita Singh|date=7 November 2008|accessdate=7 November 2008 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Reactions from politicians and the media===\nFifteen [[Member of Parliament|MP]]s signed a motion in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], tabled by Labour MP [[Andrew MacKinlay]] and Conservative MP [[Nigel Evans]], calling for Brand and Ross to no longer be funded by the [[licence fee#United Kingdom|licence fee]] (which funds the BBC). The chairman of the House of Commons [[Culture, Media and Sport Committee|select committee on culture, media and sport]], [[John Whittingdale]], stated that an investigation by the BBC was needed, but stopped short of calling for Ross and Brand to be sacked.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC should 'take some pain' for phone prank, says Will Wyatt|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Leigh Holmwood|date=28 October 2008|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/28/bbc-russell-brand|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref> The chairman of the [[House of Lords]] Select Committee on Communication, [[Norman Fowler, Baron Fowler|Lord Fowler]], in a letter to The Times (see Fowler in [[#Further reading|Further reading]]) stated that there were fundamental flaws in the way that the BBC was regulated and governed, and that there was \"confusion all round\" because two parallel bodies, the [[BBC Trust]] and Ofcom, were investigating the incident, and it was both unclear which of them the public should complain to and which of them had precedence over the other.<ref name=Times1>{{cite news|title=Russell Brand falls on his sword and a sorry Ross is taken off the air|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|author1=Patrick Foster |author2=Philip Webster |author3=Adam Sherwin |author4=Charlene Sweeney  |last-author-amp=yes |date=30 October 2008|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk./tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5042843.ece}}</ref>\n\nShadow [[Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport|Culture Secretary]] [[Jeremy Hunt]], speaking on the Radio 4 [[Today Programme]] on 30 October, also refused to say whether he thought Ross should be sacked, asserting that politicians should remain at \"arm's length\" from such decisions. In a speech at the [[London School of Economics]] the previous day he had criticised the decision by the BBC to broadcast the programme, which had been recorded 2 days prior to its transmission, saying that \"[t]he BBC was quite wrong to take the decision to broadcast the offensive phone calls\". He also demurred about calling for the resignations of anyone in BBC management, saying that \"[i]t is wrong, in principle, for politicians to be calling for heads of individual broadcasting to be removed\", and criticised the BBC for not releasing the name of the person who had given the green light for the show to be broadcast.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://walesonline.co.uk./showbiz-and-lifestyle/news/2008/10/30/steve-coogan-speaks-out-about-brand-and-ross-91466-22148936/|title=Steve Coogan speaks out about Brand and Ross|date=30 October 2008|author=Robin Turner|work=[[WalesOnline]]|publisher=Media Wales Ltd}}</ref><ref name=NewStatesman1>{{cite news|title=Tory weighs into Ross/Brand row|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2008/10/ross-brand-bbc-hunt-public|date=29 October 2008|author=Brittany Peats|work=[[New Statesman]]}}</ref>\n\nHunt was speaking to the LSE about socially responsible broadcasting, and stated \"I do think the BBC is a socially responsible broadcaster, I just think we need to hear that.\"  He argued that broadcasters were not being ambitious enough, and outlined his party's plans, should it be elected to government at the next general election, to relax regulation for those broadcasters who agreed to provide only socially responsible output. In addition to citing the Ross/Brand/Sachs affair as a \"perfect example\" of where such a \"responsibility deal\" could have operated, he also pointed to [[Channel 4]] as an example, stating that it was \"not good enough\" for it to produce \"worthy\" programmes such as [[Dispatches (TV series)|''Dispatches'']] documenting alcohol abuse in the US, whilst at the same time it was broadcasting programmes such as ''[[Hollyoaks]]'' where such abuse took up, according to his estimates, 18% of screen time. The culture spokesman for the Liberal Democrats, [[Don Foster, Baron Foster of Bath|Don Foster]], criticised this idea, stating that it threatened the very foundational principles of freedom and independence of British media, arguing that such government interference in television programming would be \"a very sad day for British broadcasting\", and pointing out that regulatory mechanisms already exist to deal with issues such as this.<ref name=NewStatesman1 /><ref>{{cite news|title=Tories mull responsible TV incentives|author=Ian Darby|url=http://brandrepublic.com./News/858123/Tories-mull-responsible-TV-incentives/|date=30 October 2008|publisher=Haymarket Media|work=Brand Republic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Responsibility contract' would threaten media freedom, say Lib Dems|author=Mark Sweney|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=29 October 2008|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|url=http://guardian.co.uk./politics/2008/oct/29/liberaldemocrats-television}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 October, Conservative MP [[Nadine Dorries]] had already called for the BBC to terminate the contracts of both Ross and Brand, and in the Commons [[David Hanson (politician)|David Hanson]] had criticised the comments for being inappropriate and not \"in keeping with broadcasting\".<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC on defensive and Ofcom steps in as 10,000 complain about Brand and Ross|author=Owen Gibson|date=29 October 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/29/russell-brand-jonathan-ross-bbc}}</ref> The conservative journalist [[Charles Moore (journalist)|Charles Moore]] announced he would not pay his television licence after the BBC's failure to sack Ross,<ref>Charles Moore [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/may/11/charles-moore-fined-tv-licence \"The BBC was too scared to sack Jonathan Ross, so the obscenity goes on\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 22 November 2008</ref> a decision which eventually led to Moore being fined in May 2010.<ref>James Robinson [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/may/11/charles-moore-fined-tv-licence \"Charles Moore fined for Jonathan Ross-inspired TV licence boycott\"], ''The Guardian'', 11 May 2010</ref>\n\nSecretary of State for Justice [[Jack Straw]], writing in his local newspaper the ''[[Lancashire Telegraph]]'' on 30 October (see Straw in [[#Further reading|Further reading]]), became the first Cabinet Minister to call for the pair to be sacked, arguing that if both presenters had worked in [[Independent Local Radio|local radio]] \"they'd have been given their [[P45 (tax)|P45]] before you could say 'Jack Robinson'.\"<ref name=Times1 /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blackburncitizen.co.uk/news/3801342.Sack_Jonathan_Ross__say_East_Lancashire_MPs/|date=30 October 2008|title=Sack Jonathan Ross, say East Lancashire MPs Jack Straw and Nigel Evans|work=[[The Citizen (Blackburn)|The Citizen]]|location=Blackburn|publisher=Newsquest Media Group}}</ref>\n\nOn the same day, Shadow Leader of the House of Commons and future Prime Minister, [[Theresa May]], called for a Commons debate on the BBC's handling of the affair.<ref>{{cite news|title=New exit in Russell Brand row as Jonathan Ross suspended unpaid|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk./tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5050293.ece|author1=Nico Hines  |author2=Philippe Naughton |lastauthoramp=yes |work=[[The Times]]|location=London|publisher=News International Limited}}</ref>\n\n===Reaction against censures and suspensions===\nIn the days following the suspensions, a number of celebrities, particularly from television and radio, came out in support of Brand and Ross. Many felt that, whilst the incident was unacceptable, it was not deserving of the strong criticism it received, especially when there were other issues troubling the United Kingdom.\n\nRod McKenzie, the editor of BBC Radio 1 ''[[Newsbeat]]'', observed on the BBC Editors' weblog (see [[#Further reading|Further reading]]) that audience reactions to Brand's and Ross' remarks had been polarised, noting that whilst his colleagues at [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]], [[BBC Radio 5 Live|Radio 5 Live]], television, and the [[BBC World Service]] had been seeing one thing, the younger audiences of Radio 1 had been reacting quite differently, and were broadly supportive of Ross and Brand. Some were amazed at the comments of the Prime Minister, with one person observing that \"[t]he financial markets are wrecked and all he can do is talk about a petty joke.\"  Others stated that people should \"calm down\", \"get a grip\", and that the subject had been \"blown out of all proportion\". McKenzie also characterised the reaction from the news media as containing \"anger: some genuine, some of it synthetic. Some of it comes from the BBC's usual critics.\"  He stated that for the people who worked in the media \"profile and salary-envy and [[:wikt:schadenfreude|schadenfreude]] may play a part in all this. But how many heard the original transmission and how many are responding to the newspapers' quotes or others' arguments?\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Criticism of Russell Brand and Jonathan Ross driven by 'salary envy', says BBC executive|author=Nicole Martin|date=29 October 2008|url=http://telegraph.co.uk./news/newstopics/celebritynews/3280037/Criticism-of-Russell-Brand-and-Jonathan-Ross-driven-by-salary-envy-says-BBC-executive.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\n[[Tim Shaw (presenter)|Tim Shaw]], disc jockey for [[Absolute Radio]], also supported Ross and Brand, appearing on BBC News wearing a T-shirt that read \"I back Brand.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com./International/Story?id=6139816&page=2|publisher=[[ABC News]]|title=BBC Comedians' Joke Falls Flat|author=Gabrial O'Rorke|date=29 October 2008}}</ref> The television presenter [[Paul O'Grady]] stated that the comedians' behaviour was \"well out of order\". However, he also suggested that the Prime Minister should get on with more important matters than complaining about media gossip.<ref>{{cite news|title= O'Grady: 'Move on from Ross and Brand'|date=30 October 2008|author=David Balls|work=[[DigitalSpy]]|url=http://digitalspy.co.uk./showbiz/a134098/ogrady-move-on-from-ross-and-brand.html}}</ref> [[Carol McGiffin]], a presenter on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s [[Daytime television|daytime]] programme ''[[Loose Women]]'' similarly supported the pair, criticising those who complained and stating that she could not wait to download the official [[podcast]] which included the incident.<ref>{{cite episode |title=[[Loose Women]] |network=[[ITV1]] |airdate=27 October 2008 |minutes=60 }}</ref>\n\n[[Noel Gallagher]] of the group [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]], a friend Brand's, complained that the press had \"dictated the tone\" of the controversy, and thought it \"typical of the English in general\" when \"10,000 people get outraged, but only days after it has happened\". Gallagher claimed to have spoken to Brand, who told Gallagher he was \"going to fall on his sword\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Oasis' Noel Gallagher 'outraged' at Russell Brand BBC scandal|work=[[NME]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://www.nme.com/news/oasis/40735}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC|date=30 October 2008|title=Oasis star backs radio pal Brand|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7699623.stm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[Digital Spy]]|title=Gallagher 'outraged' by Brand resignation|author=Alex Fletcher|url=http://digitalspy.co.uk./showbiz/a134117/gallagher-outraged-by-brand-resignation.html?id=134117&id=134117|publisher=Digital Spy Limited|date=30 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nA petition on the GoPetition web site, calling for the BBC \"to turn blame on the '[[Andrew Sachs]]' incident away from [[Russell Brand]] and [[Jonathan Ross]], and instead onto whoever green lighted the show\" had garnered a mere 336 signatures by 29 October. At the same time, a similar group on Facebook had over 1,000 members.<ref>{{cite news|title=Petition supports Brand and Ross|date=29 October 2008|work=[[Web User]]|url=http://webuser.co.uk./news/news.php?id=270991}}</ref>  By 30 October, the petition had risen to 4,000 signatures and the Facebook group to 15,609 members.<ref name=Conlan1>{{cite news|title=Brand-Ross Facebook supporters to protest outside Daily Mail|author=Tara Conlan|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/31/facebook-jonathan-ross|date=31 October 2008}}</ref> By 2 November, the Facebook group had over 30,000 members,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/entertainment/No-laughing-matter-as-.4652344.jp|title=Have you heard the one about the gagged comedians?|last=Horne|first=Marc|date=2 November 2008|work=The Scotsman|accessdate=2 November 2008|location=Edinburgh}}</ref> which had risen to over 43,000 members by 5 November.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dancer in Sachs prank criticises BBC response|author=Owen Gibson|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=6 November 2008|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/nov/06/bbc-ross-brand-georgina-baillie}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October, fans of Ross and Brand protested outside of the offices of the BBC. On 31 October, fans prepared to hold a protest outside of the offices of the ''Daily Mail'' and of the BBC.<ref name=Conlan1 />\n\nComedian [[Jimmy Carr]] also expressed his support for Ross, saying the issue had been blown out of proportion, and blamed the media themselves for escalating it further, stating that Ross was a \"national treasure\".<ref>{{cite news | title=Ross pulls out of Comedy Awards | date=31 October 2008 | url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7702309.stm | publisher =BBC News | accessdate = 31 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nFormer celebrity publicist [[Max Clifford]] played down the apparent outrage aimed at Brand. In an interview he said \"I don't think this will cause any problems for Russell Brand. He's known to be controversial and, if anything, it will make him more popular amongst his fans, who will have thought this was hilarious...They won't see anything wrong in what he did. It is a big PR success for him...He will have no problem with his career.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/3288422/Russell-Brand-controversy-will-only-increase-his-popularity-experts-say.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|author=Anita Singh|date=31 October 2008|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|title=Russell Brand controversy will only increase his popularity, experts say | location=London}}</ref>\n\nTV critic and columnist [[Charlie Brooker]] stated on his show, ''[[Charlie Brooker's Screenwipe]]'', his worry that the controversy would lead to a [[Chilling effect (term)|chilling effect]] on comedy, and that the BBC and others would self-censor too much in future. He went on to say that the attitude displayed by the complainants and the BBC's backing down would have, in earlier times, precluded the production of much of what was at the time edgy comedy and made culture poorer for it (citing ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'', ''[[The Day Today]]'' and ''[[The Young Ones (TV series)|The Young Ones]]'' amongst others as shows that would have not been commissioned owing to their controversial content). While pouring scorn on those who had complained without seeing the programme, and attacking newspapers that attempted to stir up further controversy (in particular the ''[[Daily Mail]]''), he did not appear to defend Brand and Ross in particular, stating that the possibility of people being offended by some misjudged humour is \"the price you pay for freedom of speech.\" In a further column in ''[[The Guardian]]'', he reiterated this point as well as saying that \"people who retrospectively complain to Ofcom about material they've only read about second-hand are, in essence, a bunch of sanctimonious crybabies indulging in a wretched form of masturbation.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Charlie Brooker's screen burn|date=29 November 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2008/nov/29/charlie-brooker-screen-burn-tv | location=London | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC website\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7698477.stm|title= Prank row: Georgina Baillie's reaction|date=29 October 2008|publisher=BBC|accessdate=7 November 2008}}</ref><ref name ='publicityparadox'>{{cite news|author=Matthew Taylor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/30/russell-brand-ross-baillie-sachs |title=Georgina Baillie: the Satanic Slut at the centre of the Ross-Brand controversy |work=The Guardian |date= 30 October 2008|accessdate=22 August 2010 | location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"BroadcastFiveTV\">{{cite news|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/2008/10/five_to_air_doc_on_russell_and_ross.html|title=Five to air doc on Russell and Ross|work=Broadcast|date=31 October 2008|accessdate =2 November 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7710341.stm|title=Radio 2 row 'out of proportion'|publisher=BBC News|date=7 November 2008|accessdate =7 November 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Reaction from Georgina Baillie===\n\n====Interviews====\nReacting to the suspension of [[Russell Brand]] and [[Jonathan Ross]] on 29 October, Baillie remarked: \"I'm thrilled because justice has been done...It's despicable. Calling me that in public, not only does it damage my relationship with my granddad but it could permanently damage my life as well,\" despite having declared apathy to the sentiment referenced in the latter sentence on her Myspace page.<ref name=\"BBC website\"/><ref name=\"publicityparadox\"/>\n\nA week later, on 5 November 2008, UK television channel [[Five (TV channel)|Five]] broadcast an hour-length documentary on the incident, titled ''Russell & Ross: What the F*** Was All That About?'' featuring an exclusive interview with Baillie.<ref name=\"BroadcastFiveTV\"/> Baillie stated in the interview that \"I think it's way out of proportion what's happened and I don't hate either of them \u2013 I don't at all\", going on to say \"I think they're really talented comedians and I think a world without [[Jonathan Ross]] and [[Russell Brand]] would be a very sad, dull place.\" She concluded by saying that Brand needed to learn about respecting women, while Ross should just think before he speaks, \"I don't have any harder feeling than that.\"<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Baillie also made clear that she would not object to the reinstatement of both Brand and Ross.<ref name=Barber/>\n\nOn 14 May 2009, Baillie was a guest on the BBC politics and current affairs programme ''[[This Week (BBC One TV series)|This Week]]''. She was questioned by host [[Andrew Neil]] and regular guests [[Michael Portillo]] and [[Diane Abbott]] about the Brand row within discussion of the general subject of the present day worth and genuineness of public figures saying sorry, in the wake of public apologies from members of parliament (MP's) and Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]] following the events of the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|MP's expenses row]]. Asked by Neil if receiving an apology from Brand and Ross had mattered to her, she said yes, as she had been \"publicly offended and humiliated\", and her grandfather \"had been humiliated too\". When asked by Abbott if all the publicity surrounding the Brand row had helped her career, she responded \"not necessarily ... one would think so, but not really.\" Neil further asked if the apology she received had helped, she replied yes, stating \"definitely\" to the follow-up comment from Neil of \"better to get it than not get it?\" When asked finally on the row by Neil if she thought the apologies from Brand and Ross were genuine, she replied that she thought Ross' was, but the fact that Brand had joked about the row on his later tour negated his apology.\n\n{{section move from|date=January 2020}}\n====Songwriting====\nIn 2010, Baillie teamed up with singer [[Adam Ant]] (whose drummer Hayley Leggs had been a member, alongside Baillie, of [[burlesque]] troupe The Satanic Sluts) to compose the song Gun in Your Pocket, about Ross, Brand and the entire affair, which he intended to release as the lead single for his ninth album ''[[Adam Ant Is the Blueblack Hussar in Marrying the Gunner's Daughter]]'' (with a rerecording of early 1980s outtake Who's A Goofy Bunny Then? as the B-side in tribute to the recently deceased [[Malcolm McLaren]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/04165-adam-ant-interview-oasis-lady-gaga-madonna-punk |title=Features &#124; A Wild Nobility: An Adam Ant Exclusive By Simon Price |publisher=The Quietus |accessdate=22 August 2010}}</ref> The project was put on hold when Ant (who has a history of [[bipolar disorder]] and was widely suspected around this time to have been undergoing a fresh [[Bipolar disorder#Manic episodes|manic]] episode)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.holymoly.com/celebrity-news/adam-ants-comeback-all-delusion45650 |title=Adam Ant's comeback \"all delusion\" &#124; Celebrity News |publisher=Holy Moly! |date=21 April 2010 |accessdate=22 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712214236/http://www.holymoly.com/celebrity-news/adam-ants-comeback-all-delusion45650 |archivedate=12 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> was once again [[involuntary commitment|sectioned]] on 18 May 2010 However he soon resumed his comeback and Gun in Your Pocket was finally released in October 2012 as the B-side to Cool Zombie, the eventual first single from the album (which finally emerged in January 2013).  \n\nBaillie and Ant composed a second track about the Ross-Brand affair, Rubber Medusa, a song focussed mainly on Brand and written from Baillie's perspective.  Baillie's band, the [[Fiona Bevan#Poussez Posse|Poussez Posse]], performed this second song regularly in live support slots for Ant's UK, mainland European and Australian tours during 2011\u20132012.  Commenting on the two songs in an interview by [[John Robb (musician)|John Robb]], Baillie noted \"The first one that Adam and I wrote was about an ex of mine- guess who! Which is not on the album, which is called Gun in Your Pocket ...(Subsequently) the first one Adam and I wrote together was Rubber Medusa, which was about Russell, Adam came up with the title which is a quote from the [[Jubilee (1978 film)|Jubilee]] film, [Brand] does look like a rubber [[Medusa]] so I see why he said it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://louderthanwar.com/25352/|title=Georgie Girl and her Poussez Posse : interview|work=Louder Than War}}</ref>\n\n===Support for Lesley Douglas===\nA number of radio personalities employed by the BBC came out in support of [[Lesley Douglas]], after her resignation. Douglas was aware of the contents of the programme, but had not heard them before they were broadcast. She sanctioned its broadcast with a single word e-mail of \"Yes\" sent from her [[BlackBerry]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/nov/25/lesleydouglas-bbc | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Lesley Douglas to join Universal Music | first=John | last=Plunkett | date=25 November 2008 | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref> Amongst her supporters were [[Chris Evans (presenter)|Chris Evans]] and [[Terry Wogan]], both of whom worked for BBC Radio 2 at the time, and Dame [[Liz Forgan]], who called her one of the \"outstanding broadcasters of her generation\", and said that the BBC had \"lost its wits\". Mark Thompson said that because of her knowledge of the broadcast, she had to shoulder some of the responsibility.<ref name=Notover/>\n\n===Subsequent appearances by Brand and Ross===\nRoss had been scheduled to host the 2008 [[British Comedy Awards]] for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] during the period of his suspension from the BBC; however, on 31 October he stepped down.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ross steps down from awards show|work=[[Shropshire Star]]|url=http://shropshirestar.com./2008/10/31/bbc-suspends-jonathan-ross/|date=31 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=Tara Conlan|title=Jonathan Ross pulls out of hosting British Comedy Awards|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/31/jonathan-ross-itv|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher='Guardian News and Media Limited|date=31 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 October, Brand left the country, saying that he had work to do in America, including TV programmes and film collaborations with [[Judd Apatow]] and [[Helen Mirren]].<ref name=Notover/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7703014.stm|title=Brand to film with Helen Mirren|publisher=BBC News|date=1 November 2008|accessdate=1 November 2008}}</ref> The second series of Brand's [[Channel 4]] television show ''[[Russell Brand's Ponderland]]'' aired as normal on the previous evening, attracting 1 million viewers, the show's largest ever audience. A further 180,000 watched the show time-shifted on the Channel 4+1 [[timeshift channel]]. The first series of ''Ponderland'', aired in October 2007, had been watched by 840,000 viewers, including those watching Channel 4+1. The channel reported that it had received 164 complaints from the public, many of these criticising the decision to broadcast the programme, rather than a reflection on the content, and the majority before the programme was transmitted; the show also attracted 212 emails and phone-calls of praise from fans and as such was the most praised programme screened on [[Channel 4]] for that month.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brand praised for Ponderland|publisher=broadcastnow.co.uk|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/2008/11/brand_praised_for_ponderland.html|date=5 November 2008}}</ref><ref name=Holmwood1>{{cite news|title=TV ratings: Russell Brand's post-Sachsgate TV debut bags 1m viewers|author=Leigh Holmwood|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited|date=31 October 2008|url=http://guardian.co.uk./media/2008/oct/31/tvratings-russell-brand}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://digitalspy.co.uk./tv/a134243/brands-ponderland-draws-1m.html|title=Brand's 'Ponderland' draws 1m|work=[[Digital Spy]]|date=31 October 2008|author=Neil Wilkes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Channel 4 viewers unfazed by Brand|url=http://www.metro.co.uk./fame/article.html?Channel_4_viewers_unfazed_by_Brand&in_article_id=382486|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|date=31 October 2008|publisher=Associated Newspapers Limited}}</ref>\n\nBrand similarly continued to be on the front cover of [[PETA]]'s \"Vegetarian Starter Kit\" booklet, despite people protesting to the organisation. PETA's director, Robbie LeBlanc, said that Brand, who had previously won PETA's Sexiest Vegetarian Celebrity contest twice, would remain on the cover \"because Mr Sachs, who is also a PETA supporter, has accepted Mr Brand's apology, and that's good enough for us.\"<ref>{{cite news|title= Russell Brand Wins Support of PETA Over BBC Prank Scandal|author=Jason Gregory|work=[[Gigwise]]|url=http://gigwise.com./news/47193/Russell-Brand-Wins-Support-Of-PETA-Over-BBC-Prank-Scandal|date=31 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nme.com./news/russell-brand/40766|title=PETA to stand by Russell Brand despite BBC ban|work=[[NME]]|date=31 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nBrand went on to win the British Comedy Award for Best Live Standup Performer. In his acceptance speech, Brand dedicated his award to Ross.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brand wins British Comedy Award|publisher=BBC|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7769652.stm|date=7 December 2008|accessdate =1 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter being taken off the air due to Ross' suspension, ''[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]'' returned to [[BBC One]] on 23 January 2009, featuring guests [[Tom Cruise]], [[Lee Evans (comedian)|Lee Evans]] and [[Stephen Fry]]. The show was watched by 5.1 million viewers, an increase from the 3.74 million of the last show before going off air. Ross' return attracted 25 complaints and 3 messages of support to the BBC.<ref name=\"BBC24Jan09\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7849582.stm |title=Ross TV return is watched by 5.1m |date=24 January 2009 |accessdate=27 January 2009 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, ''[[Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]'' was nominated for a BAFTA. According to ''[[The Times]]'', Ross was nominated soon after he was banned.<ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Patrick|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5971275.ece|title=BBC banned offensive Ross, then put him up for a Bafta|work=The Times|date=25 March 2009|accessdate=26 March 2009 | location=London}}</ref> Melody Sachs complained about Ross being nominated so soon after the controversy in an interview with ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', saying: \"I am amazed that Ross should get rewarded with a mouth like his. Nobody is saying he hasn't got talent, but what he did was so disgusting. Of course he is not worth the money, but he is good at his job. However, I don't think he should be rewarded so soon after what happened. It is like people are saying, 'Let's forget all about it and see what we can give him.' It is wrong and bad timing to give or even put up this guy for recognition when he has done such a terrible thing. It was unforgivable, really. I'm not angry, I just don't believe it.\"<ref name=\"DT BAFTA\">{{cite news|last=Singh|first=Anita|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/5043185/Baftas-family-of-Andrew-Sachs-flabbergasted-by-Jonathan-Ross-nomination.html|title=Baftas: family of Andrew Sachs 'flabbergasted' by Jonathan Ross nomination|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=24 March 2009|accessdate=24 March 2009 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nSachs himself said that the nomination was: \"a bit of a surprise\", and that: \"One would question the reasons when it comes so quickly after what happened. I wonder how much it has to do with trying to comfort him. I don't know. That is how it happens. That is showbusiness.\"<ref name=\"DT BAFTA\"/>\n\n==BBC Trust ruling==\nOn 21 November 2008, the BBC's watchdog [[BBC Trust]] said that the phone calls were a \"deplorable intrusion with no editorial justification.\"<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationDeplorable\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=Jonathan Ross and Russell Brand's lewd calls to actor Andrew Sachs were a \"deplorable intrusion with no editorial justification\", the BBC Trust has said.}}</ref> The Trust found that the existing BBC guidelines should have been sufficient to have prevented the incident, and that the \"very offensive\" programme should \"never have been recorded.\"<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationFailures\"/> It found the failures lay in mistakes made by BBC editorial and compliance management.<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationFailures\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=Referring to the incident, BBC trustee Richard Tait said three main failures were made \u2013 in exercising editorial control; in following established compliance systems and a failure of judgment in taking editorial decisions. He said the furore could have been avoided if BBC management had followed the corporation's editorial guidelines. \"It is a catalogue of editorial and management failures,\" he added. \"It was a very offensive programme which should never have been recorded. Once the offensive phone call was made, the recording should have stopped and senior management alerted,\" he said. }}</ref> The Trust gave its backing to the BBC's response to the incident and Ross' 12-week suspension.<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationBBCActions\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=However, he said the trust considered the BBC's response to the controversy to have been appropriate. Asked if any further action would be taken against Jonathan Ross, Sir Michael said: \"We are very clear that the director general has taken the right action with respect to Jonathan Ross.\"}}</ref>\n\nEchoing the findings of the BBC Trust, the BBC itself stated the incident was a \"very, very serious failure in a radio programme where editorial judgement was exercised that seriously let the BBC down.\"<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationDeplorableBBCResponse\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=The BBC said in a statement \"It was a very, very serious failure in a radio programme where editorial judgement was exercised that seriously let the BBC down,\"\n}}</ref>\n\nThe Trust also criticised Brand's \"so-called apology\" of 25 October, and the staff of [[Chris Moyles]]' BBC Radio 1 show for also breaching BBC guidelines for comments by Brand in an interview on the morning of 21 October at a time when children were likely to be listening.<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationDeplorableBrandActions\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=Mr Tait said the offence of the original broadcast was compounded by Russell Brand's appearance on Chris Moyles' Radio 1 show on 21 October. He said this discussion, in itself, was also in breach of editorial guidelines in respect of privacy, offence and the fact it was broadcast at a time when children were likely to be listening. Mr Tait added that the trust considered Brand's \"unacceptable, so-called apology\" broadcast on Radio 2 on 25 October \"exacerbated the intrusion into privacy and the offence\". The trust ... recommended ... that there should be tighter controls on shows made by companies owned by their performers. Brand's show was made by his own firm.}}</ref> The Trust recommended tighter controls for programmes such as Brand's, made by companies owned by their performers.<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationDeplorableBrandActions\"/> Long-term effects of the controversy would include the setting up of a register of high-risk programmes.<ref name=\"BBC21Nov2008NoJustificationDeplorableRiskResgister\">{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7741322.stm|title= 'No justification' for Brand show|publisher= [[BBC]]|date= 21 November 2008|accessdate= 21 November 2008|quote=Steps taken to ensure there is no repeat of the incident include creating a register of high-risk programmes.}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite news|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/tv_and_radio/article5023135.ece|title=Transcript: 'offensive' Brand and Ross calls|work=[[The Times]]|date=27 October 2008 | location=London | accessdate=23 May 2010 |first1=Charles |last1=Bremner |first2=David |last2=Robertson}}\n* {{cite news|title=Jonathan Ross and Russell Brand: past controversies|author=Nicole Martin|date=29 October 2008|url=http://telegraph.co.uk./news/3280359/Jonathan-Ross-and-Russell-Brand-past-controversies.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}\n* {{cite news|title=Ross and Brand, the bigger picture|author=Lord Fowler|authorlink=Norman Fowler|work=[[The Times]]|location=London|date=30 October 2008|url=http://timesonline.co.uk./tol/comment/letters/article5040972.ece}}\n* {{cite news|author=Jack Straw|authorlink=Jack Straw|title=The issues over standards at the BBC|work=[[Lancashire Telegraph]]|date=30 October 2008|url=http://lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/comment/3804407.The_issues_over_standards_at_the_BBC/|publisher=Newsquest Media Group}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk./blogs/theeditors/2008/10/open_and_shut_case.html |author= Rod McKenzie |publisher= BBC |title= Open and shut case? |date= 29 October 2008 |accessdate= 29 October 2008}}\n*{{cite web |title= And if Russell Brand and Jonathan Ross had been newspaper journalists? |website= journalism.co.uk |date= 30 October 2008 |url= http://www.journalism.co.uk/6/articles/532679.php |accessdate= 30 October 2008 |author= Martin Moore |publisher= Mousetrap Media Ltd}}\n* {{cite news |author=Mark Lawson|work=[[The Guardian]] |title= Welcome to the Blander Broadcasting Corporation |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |date=30 October 2008 |url=http://guardian.co.uk./commentisfree/2008/oct/30/bbc-jonathan-ross-russell-brand}}\n* {{cite news |author= India Knight |work= [[The Times]] |url= http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/india_knight/article5062837.ece?Submitted=true |title= Pity the women who come within range of Brand and Ross |location= London |date= 2 November 2008 | accessdate= 23 May 2010|author-link= India Knight }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/03_04_09_russelbrand.pdf Ofcom ruling on the incident]\n\n{{Russell Brand}}\n{{BBC Radio 2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russell Brand Show prank telephone calls row, The}}\n[[Category:2008 in radio]]\n[[Category:2008 in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:BBC controversies]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 2]]\n[[Category:Entertainment scandals]]\n[[Category:Prank calling]]\n[[Category:Friday Night with Jonathan Ross]]\n[[Category:Radio controversies]]\n", "name_user": "JoeSouthwood-", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReaction against censures and suspensions:typo fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Russell_Brand_Show_prank_telephone_calls_row"}
{"title_page": "Vijay Deverakonda", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian film actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vijay Deverakonda \n| image              = Vijay Deverakonda at NOTA pressmeet.jpg\n| caption            = Vijay Devarakonda at ''[[NOTA (film)| NOTA]]'' press meet in 2018\n| birth_name         = Deverakonda Vijay Sai<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ravi |first1=Murali |title=Vijay Deverakonda changes his name! To what? |url=https://www.tollywood.net/vijay-deverakonda-changes-his-name-to-what/ |accessdate=2 February 2020 |work=Tollywood |date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1989|5|9|df=y}}<ref name=\"timesofindia\">{{cite news|title=Vijay Deverakonda celebrates his birth in a unique way|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/vijay-devarakonda-celebrates-his-birthday-in-a-unique-way/articleshow/64093479.cms|website=[[The Times of India]] |author=Shalini J. R. |date=9 May 2018 |accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = \n| nationality        = Indian\n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = {{hlist|Film actor|film producer|media personality|businessperson}}\n| mother             = \n| father             = \n| family             = \n| years_active       = 2011 \u2013 present\n}}\n'''Vijay Deverakonda''' is an Indian film actor, film producer, and media personality known predominantly for his works in [[Telugu language]] films.<ref name=c>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/this-film-came-at-the-right-time/article6902995.ece|title=This film came at the right time|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=30 August 2017|date=17 February 2015|last1=Chowdhary|first1=Y. Sunita}}</ref> He debuted in 2011 with [[Ravi Babu]]'s romantic comedy ''[[Nuvvila]]'' (2011), but he gained recognition with his supporting role in the coming-of-age drama ''[[Yevade Subramanyam]]'' (2015). Vijay gained stardom by playing the lead role in the 2016 [[romantic comedy]] ''[[Pelli Choopulu]]'', which won the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Telugu]] and the [[Filmfare Award for Best Film - Telugu]]. \n\nSubsequently, Vijay has established himself as a leading actor of [[Telugu cinema]] by starring in lead roles in critical and commercial successes such as ''[[Arjun Reddy]]'' (2017), ''[[Mahanati]]'' (2018), ''[[Geetha Govindam]]'' (2018), and ''[[Taxiwaala]]'' (2018), some of which rank among the [[list of highest-grossing Telugu films]]. His performance in ''[[Arjun Reddy]]'' won him several accolades, including the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor - Telugu]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/leisure/story/20171002-vijay-sai-deverakonda-telugu-cinema-arjun-reddy-sandeep-reddy-vanga-1049492-2017-09-23|title=Serial kisser Deverakonda is the Emraan Hashmi of Telugu cinema|first1=Mona |last1=Ramavat|date=23 September 2017|website=India Today|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=a>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_pqngUO_pP4|title=Yevade Subramanyam Theatrical Trailer - Nani, Malavika Nair|last=Vyjayanthi Network|date=15 January 2015|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> In 2019, he won the [[South Indian International Movie Awards|South Indian International Movie Critics Award for Best Actor]] and was also nominated for the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor - Telugu]] for his work in  ''[[Geetha Govindam]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=P Kirubhakar |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/siima-2019-vijay-deverakonda-and-keerthy-suresh-win-big-see-pics-1581463-2019-08-16 |title=SIIMA 2019: Vijay Deverakonda and Keerthy Suresh win big. See pics - Movies News |publisher=Indiatoday.in |date= |accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe owns a film production company, King of the Hill Entertainment and was featured by ''[[Forbes India|Forbes india]]'' in their [[Forbes 30 Under 30|30 Under 30]] list of 2019.<ref name=\"ProductionHouse\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forbesindia.com/thirtyprofile2019/vijay-deverakonda/1755/21|title=Vijay Deverakonda - Forbes India Magazine|website=Forbes India|language=en|access-date=11 November 2019}}</ref> According to the annual report by the search engine Google, He was the most searched South Indian actor in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/vijay-deverakonda-is-the-most-searched-south-indian-actor-in-2019/articleshow/72490028.cms|title=Vijay Deverakonda is the most-searched South Indian actor in 2019 - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDeverakonda says, his family used to call him a ''rowdy'' every time he did something not approved by them. Over time, he started to use the term for himself and his fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/telugu/2018/jul/17/homegrown-actor-vijay-deverakonda-redefines-rowdy-1844400.html|title=Homegrown actor Vijay Deverakonda redefines 'Rowdy'|publisher=The Indian Express|date=17 July 2018 |accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/with-nota-vijay-devarakonda-is-all-set-to-conquer-tamil-audiences-what-makes-the-young-star-so-popular-5322251.html/amp|title=Vijay Devarakonda likes to call it 'Rowdy'|publisher=First post|date=5 October 2018 |accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n===Early career and struggle (2011\u20132015)===\nDeverakonda made his film debut by starring in Ravi Babu's romantic comedy [[Nuvvila]] in 2011,{{cn|date=March 2019}} and then had a small cameo role in [[Sekhar Kammula]]'s ''[[Life Is Beautiful (2012 film)|Life is Beautiful]]''. Both films were decently successful but failed to give Deverakonda much recognition.<ref name=h>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/shekhar-kammulas-telugu-film-life-is-beautiful-pushed-to-september-14-607260|title=NDTV Movies: Regional-Movies - Tamil Movies - Telugu Movies - Bengali Movies - Latest Movie News - Celebrity Gossip|website=movies.ndtv.com|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref> Then, he was introduced to an assistant director at the time, [[Nag Ashwin]], who later cast him in a supporting role for the 2015 movie ''[[Yevade Subramanyam]]'' alongside actor [[Nani (actor)|Nani]].<ref name=i>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/an-eye-for-story/article6874716.ece|title=An eye for story|newspaper=The Hindu|accessdate=30 August 2017|date=9 February 2015|last1=Chowdhary|first1=Y. Sunita}}</ref> The film was produced by the daughters of [[Ashwini Dutt]], a producer in the Telugu film industry. [[Priyanka Dutt]] backed him, and once shooting started, Swapna Dutt signed him onto her company.<ref name=j>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oSstKbH8NQg|title=Swapna Dutt Speech - Yevade Subramanyam Audio Launch Live - Nani, Malavika Nair|last=Vyjayanthi Network|date=21 February 2015|publisher=|accessdate=30 August 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref name=k>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiokhushi.com/news/details/1501/Evade-Subramanyam-says-Nani|title='Evade Subramanyam' says Nani|last=Radiokhushi|website=www.radiokhushi.com|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref> The film went on to be a critical and commercial success, and Deverakonda won high praise for his diction, energy, and role in the movie. This movie finally gave him a much-desired break in [[Telugu language|Telugu]] cinema.{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n\n===Breakthrough and success (2015\u2013present)===\nVijay's first lead role was in ''[[Pelli Choopulu]]'', a romantic coming-of-age entertainer directed by [[Tharun Bhascker Dhaassyam]], with [[Ritu Varma]] as the female lead. The film went on to be commercially successful<ref name=m>{{cite web|url=http://epaperbeta.timesofindia.com/Article.aspx?eid=31809&articlexml=VIJAY-DEVERAKONDA-SIGNS-HIS-NEXT-08062015108013|title=The Times Group|website=epaperbeta.timesofindia.com|accessdate=30 August 2017}}</ref> and won the [[National Film Award for Best Feature Film in Telugu|Best Feature Film in Telugu]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofindia.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/pelli-choopulu-bags-two-national-awards-is-best-film-in-telugu/amp_articleshow/58066962.cms|title=Pelli Choopulu bags two national awards; is 'best film' in Telugu|publisher=Times of India|date=8 April 2017}}</ref> at the [[64th National Film Awards]] as well as the [[Filmfare Award for Best Film - Telugu]]. He received praise for his realistic portrayal of a lazy and unmotivated chef.{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}} He then starred in a masala entertainer, ''[[Dwaraka (film)|Dwaraka]]'' in 2017. His next film ''[[Arjun Reddy]]'' received praise and criticism alike for being very bold and radical. Vijay's portrayal as a self-destructive, short-tempered, and alcoholic surgeon received critical acclaim, which led to him winning numerous awards, including the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor - Telugu]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/womens-groups-protest-against-arjun-reddy-vijayawada-demand-ban-films-screening-67695|title=Women's groups protest against 'Arjun Reddy' in Vijayawada, demand ban on film's screening|date=1 September 2017|work=The News Minute|access-date=3 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/movie-reviews/arjun-reddy-movie-review-intense-raw-and-unbelievably-honest-5-stars/story-kSroTBJoqiGlTBavkdlVeK.html|title=Arjun Reddy movie review: Intense, raw and unbelievably honest. 5 stars|date=26 August 2017|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=27 August 2017}}</ref> Following ''[[Arjun Reddy]]'' was ''[[Ye Mantram Vesave]]'', which was delayed for 5 years and finally released. It was given poor reviews from critics and could not fare well at the box office. He then starred in ''[[Mahanati]]'', a biographical period film around life of actress [[Savitri (actress)|Savitri]]. He won acclaim for playing a charismatic and easy going photographer. Deverakonda's next release in 2018 was [[Geetha Arts]]' romantic comedy ''[[Geetha Govindam]]'', in which he starred as an innocent and nervous college professor. Deverakonda received praise for playing a subtle, boy-next-door character after an aggressive role in Arjun Reddy. His next film, released on 5 October, was the Tamil political thriller ''[[NOTA (film)|NOTA]]'', directed by ''[[Iru Mugan]]''-fame [[Anand Shankar]]. It performed poorly at the box office.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telugu360.com/nota-worldwide-closing-collections-disaster/|title='NOTA' Worldwide Closing Collections - Disaster|date=27 October 2018|work=Telugu360.com|access-date=28 October 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> His next project was [[UV Creations]]' supernatural comedy thriller ''[[Taxiwala]]'' in which Vijay stumbles upon a possessed car opposite [[Priyanka Jawalkar]].\nIn 2019, Deverakonda was seen in [[Bharat Kamma]]'s ''[[Dear Comrade]]'', a romantic action drama, once again alongside [[Rashmika Mandanna]]. His upcoming film is [[Kranthi Madhav]]'s romantic drama titled [[World Famous Lover]] opposite [[Rashi Khanna]], [[Catherine Tresa]], [[Aishwarya Rajesh]] and [[Izabelle Leite]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/tollywood/211018/vijay-deverakondas-new-film-rolls-out.html |title=Vijay Deverakonda's new film rolls out! |publisher=Deccanchronicle.com |date= 21 October 2018|accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref> He will next be seen in Hero, a Telugu film that will be dubbed in Tamil and Malayalam too. The movie will be directed by Anand Annamalai, co-writer of films like [[Kuttrame Thandanai|Kuttramae Thandanai]] and [[Kaaka Muttai|Kaakka Muttai]]. The film see [[Malavika Mohanan]] essay the role of Vijay's love interest. Vijay will be taking on the role of a biker in this film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.in.com/entertainment/regional/vijay-devarakonda-malavika-mohanans-hero-gets-launched-biker-rajini-krishnan-to-train-the-hero-415343.htm|title=Vijay Devarakonda and Malavika Mohanan's Hero gets launched; biker Rajini Krishnan to train the Hero!|website=in.com|language=en|access-date=24 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/malavika-mohanan-and-vijay-devarakonda-in-anand-annamalais-hero/articleshow/69402713.cms|title=Malavika Mohanan and Vijay Devarakonda in Anand Annamalai's Hero|last=Coutinho|first=Natasha CoutinhoNatasha|last2=May 20|first2=Mumbai Mirror {{!}} Updated|website=Mumbai Mirror|language=en|access-date=24 May 2019|last3=2019|last4=Ist|first4=11:51}}</ref>\n\nDeverakonda was placed 72nd in the [[Forbes India]] Celebrity 100 list 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.forbesindia.com/lists/2018-celebrity-100/1735/1|title=2018 Celebrity 100|website=[[Forbes India]]|accessdate=5 December 2018}}</ref> In 2019, ''[[Film Companion]]'' ranked Deverakonda's performance in ''[[Arjun Reddy]]'' among ''100 Greatest Performances of the decade.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.filmcompanion.in/best-of-the-decade/100-best-performances-indian-cinema.html|title=100 Greatest Performances of the Decade|website=100 Greatest Performances of the Decade|language=en|access-date=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nDeverakonda made his debut in [[Hindi]] films with [[Karan Johar]] produced ''Fighter''. Directed by [[Puri Jagannadh]], the film went on floors in January 2020.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vijay Deverakonda's Hindi debut reportedly titled Fighter; Karan Johar-produced film goes on floors- Entertainment News, Firstpost |url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/vijay-deverakondas-hindi-debut-reportedly-titled-fighter-karan-johar-produced-film-goes-on-floors-7930971.html |accessdate=6 March 2020 |work=Firstpost |date=20 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===King of the Hill Entertainment===\nDeverakonda is the owner of a film production company, King of the Hill Entertainment.<ref name=\"ProductionHouse\">{{cite news |title=Vijay Deverakonda: I want to create a platform for new talent |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/telugu/vijay-deverakonda-i-want-to-create-a-platform-for-new-talent-6103938/ |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=The Indian Express |date=5 November 2019}}</ref> Its debut film,9642226257''[[Meeku Maathrame Cheptha]]'' was released in November 2019.<ref>{{cite news |title=Vijay Deverkonda Turns Producer, Announces Debut Production Meeku Maathrame Cheptha |url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/vijay-deverkonda-turns-producer-announces-film-with-meeku-maathrame-cheptha-2289531.html |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=News18 |date=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Brands and endorsements==\nOn 11 February 2020, Deverakonda launched his fashion brand \u2018Rowdy Wear\u2019 on e-commerce portal [[Myntra]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Actor Vijay Deverakonda launches his fashion brand 'Rowdy Wear' on Myntra |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/actor-vijay-deverakonda-launches-his-fashion-brand-rowdy-wear-myntra-117989 |accessdate=12 February 2020 |work=[[The News Minute]] |date=12 February 2020}}</ref> He was the brand ambassador of food delivery app [[Zomato]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Vijay Deverakonda as Zomato brand ambassador - TV9 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SQzjp60hUeo |accessdate=6 March 2020 |work=[[TV9 Telugu]] |date=22 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n\n\u2022 All the films are in [[Telugu language]], unless otherwise noted.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Film\n! Role(s)\n! Notes\n! Ref\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Nuvvila]]''\n| Vishnu\n| Film debut\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Life Is Beautiful (2012 film)|Life Is Beautiful]]''\n| Ajay\n| Villain \n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Yevade Subramanyam]]''\n| Rishi\